00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,085
CHAPTER ITHERE IS NO ONE LEFT

2
00:00:07,085 --> 00:00:11,959
When Mary Lennox was sent to MisselthwaiteManor to live with her uncle everybody said

3
00:00:11,959 --> 00:00:15,008
she was the most disagreeable-looking childever seen.

4
00:00:15,008 --> 00:00:16,054
It was true, too.

5
00:00:16,054 --> 00:00:21,009
She had a little thin face and a littlethin body, thin light hair and a sour

6
00:00:21,009 --> 00:00:21,779
expression.

7
00:00:21,779 --> 00:00:25,869
Her hair was yellow, and her face wasyellow because she had been born in India

8
00:00:25,869 --> 00:00:28,699
and had always been ill in one way oranother.

9
00:00:28,699 --> 00:00:32,769
Her father had held a position under theEnglish Government and had always been busy

10
00:00:32,769 --> 00:00:36,092
and ill himself, and her mother had been agreat beauty who cared only to go to

11
00:00:36,092 --> 00:00:39,067
parties and amuse herself with gay people.

12
00:00:39,067 --> 00:00:43,629
She had not wanted a little girl at all,and when Mary was born she handed her over

13
00:00:43,629 --> 00:00:47,299
to the care of an Ayah, who was made tounderstand that if she wished to please the

14
00:00:47,299 --> 00:00:50,589
Mem Sahib she must keep the child out ofsight as much as possible.

15
00:00:50,589 --> 00:00:55,229
So when she was a sickly, fretful, uglylittle baby she was kept out of the way,

16
00:00:55,229 --> 00:00:59,003
and when she became a sickly, fretful,toddling thing she was kept out of the way

17
00:00:59,003 --> 00:01:00,008
also.

18
00:01:00,008 --> 00:01:04,489
She never remembered seeing familiarlyanything but the dark faces of her Ayah and

19
00:01:04,489 --> 00:01:08,039
the other native servants, and as theyalways obeyed her and gave her her own way

20
00:01:08,039 --> 00:01:10,026
in everything, because the Mem Sahib would

21
00:01:10,026 --> 00:01:14,008
be angry if she was disturbed by hercrying, by the time she was six years old

22
00:01:14,008 --> 00:01:18,082
she was as tyrannical and selfish a littlepig as ever lived.

23
00:01:18,082 --> 00:01:22,076
The young English governess who came toteach her to read and write disliked her so

24
00:01:22,076 --> 00:01:26,063
much that she gave up her place in threemonths, and when other governesses came to

25
00:01:26,063 --> 00:01:30,036
try to fill it they always went away in ashorter time than the first one.

26
00:01:30,036 --> 00:01:35,027
So if Mary had not chosen to really want toknow how to read books she would never have

27
00:01:35,027 --> 00:01:37,089
learned her letters at all.

28
00:01:37,089 --> 00:01:41,085
One frightfully hot morning, when she wasabout nine years old, she awakened feeling

29
00:01:41,085 --> 00:01:46,017
very cross, and she became crosser stillwhen she saw that the servant who stood by

30
00:01:46,017 --> 00:01:48,017
her bedside was not her Ayah.

31
00:01:48,017 --> 00:01:50,051
"Why did you come?" she said to the strangewoman.

32
00:01:50,051 --> 00:01:53,093
"I will not let you stay.Send my Ayah to me."

33
00:01:53,093 --> 00:01:58,029
The woman looked frightened, but she onlystammered that the Ayah could not come and

34
00:01:58,029 --> 00:02:02,062
when Mary threw herself into a passion andbeat and kicked her, she looked only more

35
00:02:02,062 --> 00:02:04,038
frightened and repeated that it was not

36
00:02:04,038 --> 00:02:06,071
possible for the Ayah to come to MissieSahib.

37
00:02:06,071 --> 00:02:10,081
There was something mysterious in the airthat morning.

38
00:02:10,081 --> 00:02:14,002
Nothing was done in its regular order andseveral of the native servants seemed

39
00:02:14,002 --> 00:02:20,013
missing, while those whom Mary saw slunk orhurried about with ashy and scared faces.

40
00:02:20,013 --> 00:02:23,094
But no one would tell her anything and herAyah did not come.

41
00:02:23,094 --> 00:02:27,087
She was actually left alone as the morningwent on, and at last she wandered out into

42
00:02:27,087 --> 00:02:31,093
the garden and began to play by herselfunder a tree near the veranda.

43
00:02:31,093 --> 00:02:35,083
She pretended that she was making a flower-bed, and she stuck big scarlet hibiscus

44
00:02:35,083 --> 00:02:40,049
blossoms into little heaps of earth, allthe time growing more and more angry and

45
00:02:40,049 --> 00:02:42,000
muttering to herself the things she would

46
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:44,093
say and the names she would call Saidiewhen she returned.

47
00:02:44,093 --> 00:02:50,036
"Pig! Pig! Daughter of Pigs!" she said,because to call a native a pig is the worst

48
00:02:50,036 --> 00:02:52,013
insult of all.

49
00:02:52,013 --> 00:02:55,097
She was grinding her teeth and saying thisover and over again when she heard her

50
00:02:55,097 --> 00:02:58,042
mother come out on the veranda with someone.

51
00:02:58,042 --> 00:03:02,023
She was with a fair young man and theystood talking together in low strange

52
00:03:02,023 --> 00:03:05,033
voices.Mary knew the fair young man who looked

53
00:03:05,033 --> 00:03:06,055
like a boy.

54
00:03:06,055 --> 00:03:10,036
She had heard that he was a very youngofficer who had just come from England.

55
00:03:10,036 --> 00:03:13,079
The child stared at him, but she staredmost at her mother.

56
00:03:13,079 --> 00:03:17,599
She always did this when she had a chanceto see her, because the Mem Sahib--Mary

57
00:03:17,599 --> 00:03:22,052
used to call her that oftener than anythingelse--was such a tall, slim, pretty person

58
00:03:22,052 --> 00:03:24,004
and wore such lovely clothes.

59
00:03:24,004 --> 00:03:28,076
Her hair was like curly silk and she had adelicate little nose which seemed to be

60
00:03:28,076 --> 00:03:31,092
disdaining things, and she had largelaughing eyes.

61
00:03:31,092 --> 00:03:37,027
All her clothes were thin and floating, andMary said they were "full of lace."

62
00:03:37,027 --> 00:03:40,959
They looked fuller of lace than ever thismorning, but her eyes were not laughing at

63
00:03:40,959 --> 00:03:41,003
all.

64
00:03:41,003 --> 00:03:46,052
They were large and scared and liftedimploringly to the fair boy officer's face.

65
00:03:46,052 --> 00:03:49,016
"Is it so very bad?Oh, is it?"

66
00:03:49,016 --> 00:03:51,019
Mary heard her say.

67
00:03:51,019 --> 00:03:53,043
"Awfully," the young man answered in atrembling voice.

68
00:03:53,043 --> 00:03:56,051
"Awfully, Mrs. Lennox.You ought to have gone to the hills two

69
00:03:56,051 --> 00:03:58,018
weeks ago."

70
00:03:58,018 --> 00:04:02,025
The Mem Sahib wrung her hands."Oh, I know I ought!" she cried.

71
00:04:02,025 --> 00:04:04,067
"I only stayed to go to that silly dinnerparty.

72
00:04:04,067 --> 00:04:06,078
What a fool I was!"

73
00:04:06,078 --> 00:04:10,036
At that very moment such a loud sound ofwailing broke out from the servants'

74
00:04:10,036 --> 00:04:14,569
quarters that she clutched the young man'sarm, and Mary stood shivering from head to

75
00:04:14,569 --> 00:04:15,639
foot.

76
00:04:15,639 --> 00:04:19,049
The wailing grew wilder and wilder."What is it?

77
00:04:19,049 --> 00:04:21,319
What is it?"Mrs. Lennox gasped.

78
00:04:21,319 --> 00:04:24,009
"Some one has died," answered the boyofficer.

79
00:04:24,009 --> 00:04:26,052
"You did not say it had broken out amongyour servants."

80
00:04:26,052 --> 00:04:28,008
"I did not know!" the Mem Sahib cried.

81
00:04:28,008 --> 00:04:31,074
"Come with me!Come with me!" and she turned and ran into

82
00:04:31,074 --> 00:04:33,027
the house.

83
00:04:33,027 --> 00:04:37,009
After that, appalling things happened, andthe mysteriousness of the morning was

84
00:04:37,009 --> 00:04:38,499
explained to Mary.

85
00:04:38,499 --> 00:04:42,289
The cholera had broken out in its mostfatal form and people were dying like

86
00:04:42,289 --> 00:04:43,479
flies.

87
00:04:43,479 --> 00:04:47,199
The Ayah had been taken ill in the night,and it was because she had just died that

88
00:04:47,199 --> 00:04:49,419
the servants had wailed in the huts.

89
00:04:49,419 --> 00:04:53,069
Before the next day three other servantswere dead and others had run away in

90
00:04:53,069 --> 00:04:56,011
terror.There was panic on every side, and dying

91
00:04:56,011 --> 00:04:58,819
people in all the bungalows.

92
00:04:58,819 --> 00:05:02,439
During the confusion and bewilderment ofthe second day Mary hid herself in the

93
00:05:02,439 --> 00:05:04,979
nursery and was forgotten by everyone.

94
00:05:04,979 --> 00:05:08,619
Nobody thought of her, nobody wanted her,and strange things happened of which she

95
00:05:08,619 --> 00:05:12,279
knew nothing.Mary alternately cried and slept through

96
00:05:12,279 --> 00:05:13,003
the hours.

97
00:05:13,003 --> 00:05:17,069
She only knew that people were ill and thatshe heard mysterious and frightening

98
00:05:17,069 --> 00:05:18,018
sounds.

99
00:05:18,018 --> 00:05:21,099
Once she crept into the dining-room andfound it empty, though a partly finished

100
00:05:21,099 --> 00:05:25,729
meal was on the table and chairs and plateslooked as if they had been hastily pushed

101
00:05:25,729 --> 00:05:29,349
back when the diners rose suddenly for somereason.

102
00:05:29,349 --> 00:05:33,389
The child ate some fruit and biscuits, andbeing thirsty she drank a glass of wine

103
00:05:33,389 --> 00:05:34,093
which stood nearly filled.

104
00:05:34,093 --> 00:05:38,024
It was sweet, and she did not know howstrong it was.

105
00:05:38,024 --> 00:05:41,999
Very soon it made her intensely drowsy, andshe went back to her nursery and shut

106
00:05:41,999 --> 00:05:46,259
herself in again, frightened by cries sheheard in the huts and by the hurrying sound

107
00:05:46,259 --> 00:05:47,889
of feet.

108
00:05:47,889 --> 00:05:51,539
The wine made her so sleepy that she couldscarcely keep her eyes open and she lay

109
00:05:51,539 --> 00:05:55,099
down on her bed and knew nothing more for along time.

110
00:05:55,099 --> 00:05:58,889
Many things happened during the hours inwhich she slept so heavily, but she was not

111
00:05:58,889 --> 00:06:02,319
disturbed by the wails and the sound ofthings being carried in and out of the

112
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:04,169
bungalow.

113
00:06:04,169 --> 00:06:06,819
When she awakened she lay and stared at thewall.

114
00:06:06,819 --> 00:06:10,093
The house was perfectly still.She had never known it to be so silent

115
00:06:10,093 --> 00:06:12,069
before.

116
00:06:12,069 --> 00:06:16,139
She heard neither voices nor footsteps, andwondered if everybody had got well of the

117
00:06:16,139 --> 00:06:20,349
cholera and all the trouble was over.She wondered also who would take care of

118
00:06:20,349 --> 00:06:21,479
her now her Ayah was dead.

119
00:06:21,479 --> 00:06:26,319
There would be a new Ayah, and perhaps shewould know some new stories.

120
00:06:26,319 --> 00:06:31,002
Mary had been rather tired of the old ones.She did not cry because her nurse had died.

121
00:06:31,002 --> 00:06:35,229
She was not an affectionate child and hadnever cared much for any one.

122
00:06:35,229 --> 00:06:39,005
The noise and hurrying about and wailingover the cholera had frightened her, and

123
00:06:39,005 --> 00:06:41,083
she had been angry because no one seemed toremember that she was alive.

124
00:06:41,083 --> 00:06:46,729
Everyone was too panic-stricken to think ofa little girl no one was fond of.

125
00:06:46,729 --> 00:06:50,879
When people had the cholera it seemed thatthey remembered nothing but themselves.

126
00:06:50,879 --> 00:06:54,899
But if everyone had got well again, surelysome one would remember and come to look

127
00:06:54,899 --> 00:06:58,719
for her.But no one came, and as she lay waiting the

128
00:06:58,719 --> 00:07:01,055
house seemed to grow more and more silent.

129
00:07:01,055 --> 00:07:06,002
She heard something rustling on the mattingand when she looked down she saw a little

130
00:07:06,002 --> 00:07:09,046
snake gliding along and watching her witheyes like jewels.

131
00:07:09,046 --> 00:07:12,839
She was not frightened, because he was aharmless little thing who would not hurt

132
00:07:12,839 --> 00:07:15,589
her and he seemed in a hurry to get out ofthe room.

133
00:07:15,589 --> 00:07:18,069
He slipped under the door as she watchedhim.

134
00:07:18,069 --> 00:07:23,005
"How queer and quiet it is," she said."It sounds as if there were no one in the

135
00:07:23,005 --> 00:07:25,077
bungalow but me and the snake."

136
00:07:25,077 --> 00:07:29,005
Almost the next minute she heard footstepsin the compound, and then on the veranda.

137
00:07:29,005 --> 00:07:33,229
They were men's footsteps, and the menentered the bungalow and talked in low

138
00:07:33,229 --> 00:07:34,599
voices.

139
00:07:34,599 --> 00:07:38,139
No one went to meet or speak to them andthey seemed to open doors and look into

140
00:07:38,139 --> 00:07:41,479
rooms."What desolation!" she heard one voice say.

141
00:07:41,479 --> 00:07:43,569
"That pretty, pretty woman!

142
00:07:43,569 --> 00:07:46,789
I suppose the child, too.I heard there was a child, though no one

143
00:07:46,789 --> 00:07:48,959
ever saw her."

144
00:07:48,959 --> 00:07:51,639
Mary was standing in the middle of thenursery when they opened the door a few

145
00:07:51,639 --> 00:07:52,939
minutes later.

146
00:07:52,939 --> 00:07:56,439
She looked an ugly, cross little thing andwas frowning because she was beginning to

147
00:07:56,439 --> 00:07:59,389
be hungry and feel disgracefully neglected.

148
00:07:59,389 --> 00:08:02,999
The first man who came in was a largeofficer she had once seen talking to her

149
00:08:02,999 --> 00:08:03,929
father.

150
00:08:03,929 --> 00:08:08,159
He looked tired and troubled, but when hesaw her he was so startled that he almost

151
00:08:08,159 --> 00:08:10,959
jumped back."Barney!" he cried out.

152
00:08:10,959 --> 00:08:12,589
"There is a child here!

153
00:08:12,589 --> 00:08:15,309
A child alone!In a place like this!

154
00:08:15,309 --> 00:08:19,909
Mercy on us, who is she!""I am Mary Lennox," the little girl said,

155
00:08:19,909 --> 00:08:21,879
drawing herself up stiffly.

156
00:08:21,879 --> 00:08:26,055
She thought the man was very rude to callher father's bungalow "A place like this!"

157
00:08:26,055 --> 00:08:30,049
"I fell asleep when everyone had thecholera and I have only just wakened up.

158
00:08:30,049 --> 00:08:32,399
Why does nobody come?"

159
00:08:32,399 --> 00:08:35,086
"It is the child no one ever saw!"exclaimed the man, turning to his

160
00:08:35,086 --> 00:08:38,419
companions."She has actually been forgotten!"

161
00:08:38,419 --> 00:08:40,057
"Why was I forgotten?"

162
00:08:40,057 --> 00:08:43,099
Mary said, stamping her foot."Why does nobody come?"

163
00:08:43,099 --> 00:08:47,063
The young man whose name was Barney lookedat her very sadly.

164
00:08:47,063 --> 00:08:51,038
Mary even thought she saw him wink his eyesas if to wink tears away.

165
00:08:51,038 --> 00:08:55,097
"Poor little kid!" he said."There is nobody left to come."

166
00:08:55,097 --> 00:08:59,081
It was in that strange and sudden way thatMary found out that she had neither father

167
00:08:59,081 --> 00:09:04,000
nor mother left; that they had died andbeen carried away in the night, and that

168
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:05,086
the few native servants who had not died

169
00:09:05,086 --> 00:09:09,078
also had left the house as quickly as theycould get out of it, none of them even

170
00:09:09,078 --> 00:09:14,051
remembering that there was a Missie Sahib.That was why the place was so quiet.

171
00:09:14,051 --> 00:09:18,055
It was true that there was no one in thebungalow but herself and the little

172
00:09:18,055 --> 00:09:24,000
rustling snake.

