wouldn't come if he would let them.

230
00:12:25,083 --> 00:12:29,097
He's a hunchback, and he's horrid.""I don't believe you," said Mary; and she

231
00:12:29,097 --> 00:12:33,001
turned her back and stuck her fingers inher ears, because she would not listen any

232
00:12:33,001 --> 00:12:34,008
more.

233
00:12:34,008 --> 00:12:37,073
But she thought over it a great dealafterward; and when Mrs. Crawford told her

234
00:12:37,073 --> 00:12:41,459
that night that she was going to sail awayto England in a few days and go to her

235
00:12:41,459 --> 00:12:43,009
uncle, Mr. Archibald Craven, who lived at

236
00:12:43,009 --> 00:12:47,849
Misselthwaite Manor, she looked so stonyand stubbornly uninterested that they did

237
00:12:47,849 --> 00:12:49,239
not know what to think about her.

238
00:12:49,239 --> 00:12:53,044
They tried to be kind to her, but she onlyturned her face away when Mrs. Crawford

239
00:12:53,044 --> 00:12:57,006
attempted to kiss her, and held herselfstiffly when Mr. Crawford patted her

240
00:12:57,006 --> 00:12:58,319
shoulder.

241
00:12:58,319 --> 00:13:02,819
"She is such a plain child," Mrs. Crawfordsaid pityingly, afterward.

242
00:13:02,819 --> 00:13:05,001
