243
00:13:05,001 --> 00:13:09,028
She had a very pretty manner, too, and Maryhas the most unattractive ways I ever saw

244
00:13:09,028 --> 00:13:10,045
in a child.

245
00:13:10,045 --> 00:13:14,349
The children call her 'Mistress Mary QuiteContrary,' and though it's naughty of them,

246
00:13:14,349 --> 00:13:16,079
one can't help understanding it."

247
00:13:16,079 --> 00:13:20,011
"Perhaps if her mother had carried herpretty face and her pretty manners oftener

248
00:13:20,011 --> 00:13:24,001
into the nursery Mary might have learnedsome pretty ways too.

249
00:13:24,001 --> 00:13:27,909
It is very sad, now the poor beautifulthing is gone, to remember that many people

250
00:13:27,909 --> 00:13:30,799
never even knew that she had a child atall."

251
00:13:30,799 --> 00:13:33,097
"I believe she scarcely ever looked ather," sighed Mrs. Crawford.

252
00:13:33,097 --> 00:13:36,879
"When her Ayah was dead there was no one togive a thought to the little thing.

253
00:13:36,879 --> 00:13:40,009
Think of the servants running away andleaving her all alone in that deserted

254
00:13:40,009 --> 00:13:41,097
bungalow.

255
00:13:41,097 --> 00:13:45,329
Colonel McGrew said he nearly jumped out ofhis skin when he opened the door and found

256
00:13:45,329 --> 00:13:49,012
her standing by herself in the middle ofthe room."

257
00:13:49,012 --> 00:13:53,002
Mary made the long voyage to England underthe care of an officer's wife, who was

258
00:13:53,002 --> 00:13:56,006
taking her children to leave them in aboarding-school.

259
00:13:56,006 --> 00:13:59,004
She was very much absorbed in her ownlittle boy and girl, and was rather glad to

260
00:13:59,004 --> 00:14:03,008
hand the child over to the woman Mr.Archibald Craven sent to meet her, in

261
00:14:03,008 --> 00:14:04,024
London.

262
00:14:04,024 --> 00:14:07,096
The woman was his housekeeper atMisselthwaite Manor, and her name was Mrs.

263
00:14:07,096 --> 00:14:10,068
Medlock.She was a stout woman, with very red cheeks

264
00:14:10,068 --> 00:14:12,699
and sharp black eyes.

265
00:14:12,699 --> 00:14:17,036
She wore a very purple dress, a black silkmantle with jet fringe on it and a black

266
00:14:17,036 --> 00:14:21,087
bonnet with purple velvet flowers whichstuck up and trembled when she moved her

267
00:14:21,087 --> 00:14:22,043
head.

268
00:14:22,043 --> 00:14:25,091
Mary did not like her at all, but as shevery seldom liked people there was nothing

269
00:14:25,091 --> 00:14:29,889
remarkable in that; besides which it wasvery evident Mrs. Medlock did not think

270
00:14:29,889 --> 00:14:31,011
much of her.

271
00:14:31,011 --> 00:14:33,075
"My word! she's a plain little piece ofgoods!" she said.

272
00:14:33,075 --> 00:14:36,034
"And we'd heard that her mother was abeauty.

273
00:14:36,034 --> 00:14:39,169
She hasn't handed much of it down, has she,ma'am?"

274
00:14:39,169 --> 00:14:42,229
"Perhaps she will improve as she growsolder," the officer's wife said good-

275
00:14:42,229 --> 00:14:43,033
naturedly.

276
00:14:43,033 --> 00:14:47,046
"If she were not so sallow and had a nicerexpression, her features are rather good.

277
00:14:47,046 --> 00:14:51,018
Children alter so much.""She'll have to alter a good deal,"

278
00:14:51,018 --> 00:14:52,789
answered Mrs. Medlock.

279
00:14:52,789 --> 00:14:56,729
"And, there's nothing likely to improvechildren at Misselthwaite--if you ask me!"

280
00:14:56,729 --> 00:15:00,003
They thought Mary was not listening becauseshe was standing a little apart from them

281
00:15:00,003 --> 00:15:03,002
at the window of the private hotel they hadgone to.

282
00:15:03,002 --> 00:15:07,062
She was watching the passing buses and cabsand people, but she heard quite well and

283
00:15:07,062 --> 00:15:11,002
was made very curious about her uncle andthe place he lived in.

284
00:15:11,002 --> 00:15:14,759
What sort of a place was it, and what wouldhe be like?

285
00:15:14,759 --> 00:15:17,005
What was a hunchback?She had never seen one.

286
00:15:17,005 --> 00:15:20,016
Perhaps there were none in India.

287
00:15:20,016 --> 00:15:24,018
Since she had been living in other people'shouses and had had no Ayah, she had begun

288
00:15:24,018 --> 00:15:28,039
to feel lonely and to think queer thoughtswhich were new to her.

289
00:15:28,039 --> 00:15:31,096
She had begun to wonder why she had neverseemed to belong to anyone even when her

290
00:15:31,096 --> 00:15:34,015
father and mother had been alive.

291
00:15:34,015 --> 00:15:37,059
Other children seemed to belong to theirfathers and mothers, but she had never

292
00:15:37,059 --> 00:15:42,084
seemed to really be anyone's little girl.She had had servants, and food and clothes,

293
00:15:42,084 --> 00:15:45,021
but no one had taken any notice of her.

294
00:15:45,021 --> 00:15:48,081
She did not know that this was because shewas a disagreeable child; but then, of

295
00:15:48,081 --> 00:15:51,024
course, she did not know she wasdisagreeable.

296
00:15:51,024 --> 00:15:55,025
She often thought that other people were,but she did not know that she was so

297
00:15:55,025 --> 00:15:56,019
herself.

298
00:15:56,019 --> 00:15:59,569
She thought Mrs. Medlock the mostdisagreeable person she had ever seen, with

299
00:15:59,569 --> 00:16:03,058
her common, highly colored face and hercommon fine bonnet.

300
00:16:03,058 --> 00:16:07,006
When the next day they set out on theirjourney to Yorkshire, she walked through

301
00:16:07,006 --> 00:16:10,077
the station to the railway carriage withher head up and trying to keep as far away

302
00:16:10,077 --> 00:16:15,016
from her as she could, because she did notwant to seem to belong to her.

303
00:16:15,016 --> 00:16:18,509
It would have made her angry to thinkpeople imagined she was her little girl.

304
00:16:18,509 --> 00:16:22,139
But Mrs. Medlock was not in the leastdisturbed by her and her thoughts.

305
00:16:22,139 --> 00:16:25,077
She was the kind of woman who would "standno nonsense from young ones."

306
00:16:25,077 --> 00:16:28,055
At least, that is what she would have saidif she had been asked.

307
00:16:28,055 --> 00:16:32,031
She had not wanted to go to London justwhen her sister Maria's daughter was going

308
00:16:32,031 --> 00:16:35,979
to be married, but she had a comfortable,well paid place as housekeeper at

309
00:16:35,979 --> 00:16:38,139
Misselthwaite Manor and the only way in

310
00:16:38,139 --> 00:16:42,349
which she could keep it was to do at oncewhat Mr. Archibald Craven told her to do.

311
00:16:42,349 --> 00:16:45,024
She never dared even to ask a question.

312
00:16:45,024 --> 00:16:48,091
"Captain Lennox and his wife died of thecholera," Mr. Craven had said in his short,

313
00:16:48,091 --> 00:16:51,979
cold way."Captain Lennox was my wife's brother and I

314
00:16:51,979 --> 00:16:53,033
am their daughter's guardian.

315
00:16:53,033 --> 00:16:56,569
The child is to be brought here.You must go to London and bring her

316
00:16:56,569 --> 00:16:59,043
yourself."So she packed her small trunk and made the

317
00:16:59,043 --> 00:17:01,729
journey.

318
00:17:01,729 --> 00:17:05,509
Mary sat in her corner of the railwaycarriage and looked plain and fretful.

319
00:17:05,509 --> 00:17:09,044
She had nothing to read or to look at, andshe had folded her thin little black-gloved

320
00:17:09,044 --> 00:17:10,639
hands in her lap.

321
00:17:10,639 --> 00:17:15,011
Her black dress made her look yellower thanever, and her limp light hair straggled

322
00:17:15,011 --> 00:17:19,036
from under her black crepe hat."A more marred-looking young one I never

323
00:17:19,036 --> 00:17:20,097
saw in my life," Mrs. Medlock thought.

324
00:17:20,097 --> 00:17:25,012
(Marred is a Yorkshire word and meansspoiled and pettish.)

325
00:17:25,012 --> 00:17:29,033
She had never seen a child who sat so stillwithout doing anything; and at last she got

326
00:17:29,033 --> 00:17:33,449
tired of watching her and began to talk ina brisk, hard voice.

327
00:17:33,449 --> 00:17:36,041
