330
00:17:43,041 --> 00:17:45,539
"No," said Mary frowning.

331
00:17:45,539 --> 00:17:48,699
She frowned because she remembered that herfather and mother had never talked to her

332
00:17:48,699 --> 00:17:52,139
about anything in particular.Certainly they had never told her things.

333
00:17:52,139 --> 00:17:57,003
"Humph," muttered Mrs. Medlock, staring ather queer, unresponsive little face.

334
00:17:57,003 --> 00:18:00,095
She did not say any more for a few momentsand then she began again.

335
00:18:00,095 --> 00:18:03,089
"I suppose you might as well be toldsomething--to prepare you.

336
00:18:03,089 --> 00:18:05,099
You are going to a queer place."

337
00:18:05,099 --> 00:18:10,279
Mary said nothing at all, and Mrs. Medlocklooked rather discomfited by her apparent

338
00:18:10,279 --> 00:18:13,769
indifference, but, after taking a breath,she went on.

339
00:18:13,769 --> 00:18:18,018
"Not but that it's a grand big place in agloomy way, and Mr. Craven's proud of it in

340
00:18:18,018 --> 00:18:21,003
his way--and that's gloomy enough, too.

341
00:18:21,003 --> 00:18:24,086
The house is six hundred years old and it'son the edge of the moor, and there's near a

342
00:18:24,086 --> 00:18:27,083
hundred rooms in it, though most of them'sshut up and locked.

343
00:18:27,083 --> 00:18:32,013
And there's pictures and fine old furnitureand things that's been there for ages, and

344
00:18:32,013 --> 00:18:36,036
there's a big park round it and gardens andtrees with branches trailing to the ground-

345
00:18:36,036 --> 00:18:37,057
-some of them."

346
00:18:37,057 --> 00:18:42,000
She paused and took another breath."But there's nothing else," she ended

347
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:44,067
suddenly.Mary had begun to listen in spite of

348
00:18:44,067 --> 00:18:45,779
herself.

349
00:18:45,779 --> 00:18:50,042
