455
00:24:18,079 --> 00:24:21,063
When he shut the door, mounted the box withthe coachman, and they drove off, the

456
00:24:21,063 --> 00:24:25,869
little girl found herself seated in acomfortably cushioned corner, but she was

457
00:24:25,869 --> 00:24:27,067
not inclined to go to sleep again.

458
00:24:27,067 --> 00:24:31,005
She sat and looked out of the window,curious to see something of the road over

459
00:24:31,005 --> 00:24:35,045
which she was being driven to the queerplace Mrs. Medlock had spoken of.

460
00:24:35,045 --> 00:24:39,056
She was not at all a timid child and shewas not exactly frightened, but she felt

461
00:24:39,056 --> 00:24:43,026
that there was no knowing what might happenin a house with a hundred rooms nearly all

462
00:24:43,026 --> 00:24:47,003
shut up--a house standing on the edge of amoor.

463
00:24:47,003 --> 00:24:50,037
"What is a moor?" she said suddenly to Mrs.Medlock.

464
00:24:50,037 --> 00:24:53,022
"Look out of the window in about tenminutes and you'll see," the woman

465
00:24:53,022 --> 00:24:55,007
answered."We've got to drive five miles across

466
00:24:55,007 --> 00:24:57,095
Missel Moor before we get to the Manor.

467
00:24:57,095 --> 00:25:02,058
You won't see much because it's a darknight, but you can see something."

468
00:25:02,058 --> 00:25:06,037
Mary asked no more questions but waited inthe darkness of her corner, keeping her

469
00:25:06,037 --> 00:25:08,002
eyes on the window.

470
00:25:08,002 --> 00:25:11,084
The carriage lamps cast rays of light alittle distance ahead of them and she

471
00:25:11,084 --> 00:25:15,129
caught glimpses of the things they passed.

472
00:25:15,129 --> 00:25:18,058
After they had left the station they haddriven through a tiny village and she had

473
00:25:18,058 --> 00:25:22,000
seen whitewashed cottages and the lights ofa public house.

474
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:25,055
Then they had passed a church and avicarage and a little shop-window or so in

475
00:25:25,055 --> 00:25:29,069
a cottage with toys and sweets and oddthings set out for sale.

476
00:25:29,069 --> 00:25:32,069
Then they were on the highroad and she sawhedges and trees.

477
00:25:32,069 --> 00:25:37,045
After that there seemed nothing differentfor a long time--or at least it seemed a

478
00:25:37,045 --> 00:25:39,003
long time to her.

479
00:25:39,003 --> 00:25:43,008
At last the horses began to go more slowly,as if they were climbing up-hill, and

480
00:25:43,008 --> 00:25:47,269
presently there seemed to be no more hedgesand no more trees.

481
00:25:47,269 --> 00:25:51,053
She could see nothing, in fact, but a densedarkness on either side.

482
00:25:51,053 --> 00:25:54,084
She leaned forward and pressed her faceagainst the window just as the carriage

483
00:25:54,084 --> 00:25:55,007
gave a big jolt.

484
00:25:55,007 --> 00:26:00,007
"Eh! We're on the moor now sure enough,"said Mrs. Medlock.

485
00:26:00,007 --> 00:26:05,099
The carriage lamps shed a yellow light on arough-looking road which seemed to be cut

486
00:26:05,099 --> 00:26:09,003
through bushes and low-growing things whichended in the great expanse of dark

487
00:26:09,003 --> 00:26:12,003
apparently spread out before and aroundthem.

488
00:26:12,003 --> 00:26:16,239
A wind was rising and making a singular,wild, low, rushing sound.

489
00:26:16,239 --> 00:26:21,045
"It's--it's not the sea, is it?" said Mary,looking round at her companion.

490
00:26:21,045 --> 00:26:23,909
"No, not it," answered Mrs. Medlock.

491
00:26:23,909 --> 00:26:28,879
"Nor it isn't fields nor mountains, it'sjust miles and miles and miles of wild land

492
00:26:28,879 --> 00:26:33,011
that nothing grows on but heather and gorseand broom, and nothing lives on but wild

493
00:26:33,011 --> 00:26:34,199
ponies and sheep."

494
00:26:34,199 --> 00:26:39,379
"I feel as if it might be the sea, if therewere water on it," said Mary.

495
00:26:39,379 --> 00:26:42,083
"It sounds like the sea just now.""That's the wind blowing through the

496
00:26:42,083 --> 00:26:44,011
bushes," Mrs. Medlock said.

497
00:26:44,011 --> 00:26:48,539
"It's a wild, dreary enough place to mymind, though there's plenty that likes it--

498
00:26:48,539 --> 00:26:51,008
particularly when the heather's in bloom."

499
00:26:51,008 --> 00:26:55,669
On and on they drove through the darkness,and though the rain stopped, the wind

500
00:26:55,669 --> 00:26:59,309
rushed by and whistled and made strangesounds.

501
00:26:59,309 --> 00:27:03,119
The road went up and down, and severaltimes the carriage passed over a little

502
00:27:03,119 --> 00:27:07,096
bridge beneath which water rushed very fastwith a great deal of noise.

503
00:27:07,096 --> 00:27:12,096
Mary felt as if the drive would never cometo an end and that the wide, bleak moor was

504
00:27:12,096 --> 00:27:18,039
a wide expanse of black ocean through whichshe was passing on a strip of dry land.

505
00:27:18,039 --> 00:27:19,619
"I don't like it," she said to herself.

506
00:27:19,619 --> 00:27:25,199
"I don't like it," and she pinched her thinlips more tightly together.

507
00:27:25,199 --> 00:27:29,309
The horses were climbing up a hilly pieceof road when she first caught sight of a

508
00:27:29,309 --> 00:27:29,669
light.

509
00:27:29,669 --> 00:27:33,061
Mrs. Medlock saw it as soon as she did anddrew a long sigh of relief.

510
00:27:33,061 --> 00:27:37,309
"Eh, I am glad to see that bit o' lighttwinkling," she exclaimed.

511
00:27:37,309 --> 00:27:39,039
"It's the light in the lodge window.

512
00:27:39,039 --> 00:27:42,119
We shall get a good cup of tea after a bit,at all events."

513
00:27:42,119 --> 00:27:46,011
It was "after a bit," as she said, for whenthe carriage passed through the park gates

514
00:27:46,011 --> 00:27:50,099
there was still two miles of avenue todrive through and the trees (which nearly

515
00:27:50,099 --> 00:27:55,129
met overhead) made it seem as if they weredriving through a long dark vault.

516
00:27:55,129 --> 00:27:59,159
They drove out of the vault into a clearspace and stopped before an immensely long

517
00:27:59,159 --> 00:28:03,399
but low-built house which seemed to rambleround a stone court.

518
00:28:03,399 --> 00:28:07,129
At first Mary thought that there were nolights at all in the windows, but as she

519
00:28:07,129 --> 00:28:11,021
got out of the carriage she saw that oneroom in a corner upstairs showed a dull

520
00:28:11,021 --> 00:28:12,569
glow.

521
00:28:12,569 --> 00:28:16,659
The entrance door was a huge one made ofmassive, curiously shaped panels of oak

522
00:28:16,659 --> 00:28:21,027
studded with big iron nails and bound withgreat iron bars.

523
00:28:21,027 --> 00:28:25,149
It opened into an enormous hall, which wasso dimly lighted that the faces in the

524
00:28:25,149 --> 00:28:29,149
portraits on the walls and the figures inthe suits of armor made Mary feel that she

525
00:28:29,149 --> 00:28:30,099
did not want to look at them.

526
00:28:30,099 --> 00:28:35,789
As she stood on the stone floor she lookeda very small, odd little black figure, and

527
00:28:35,789 --> 00:28:39,049
she felt as small and lost and odd as shelooked.

528
00:28:39,049 --> 00:28:43,559
A neat, thin old man stood near themanservant who opened the door for them.

529
00:28:43,559 --> 00:28:46,349
"You are to take her to her room," he saidin a husky voice.

530
00:28:46,349 --> 00:28:47,869
"He doesn't want to see her.

531
00:28:47,869 --> 00:28:51,379
He's going to London in the morning.""Very well, Mr. Pitcher," Mrs. Medlock

532
00:28:51,379 --> 00:28:53,077
answered."So long as I know what's expected of me, I

533
00:28:53,077 --> 00:28:54,139
can manage."

534
00:28:54,139 --> 00:28:58,509
"What's expected of you, Mrs. Medlock," Mr.Pitcher said, "is that you make sure that

535
00:28:58,509 --> 00:29:03,021
he's not disturbed and that he doesn't seewhat he doesn't want to see."

536
00:29:03,021 --> 00:29:07,809
And then Mary Lennox was led up a broadstaircase and down a long corridor and up a

537
00:29:07,809 --> 00:29:12,319
short flight of steps and through anothercorridor and another, until a door opened

538
00:29:12,319 --> 00:29:16,649
in a wall and she found herself in a roomwith a fire in it and a supper on a table.

539
00:29:16,649 --> 00:29:20,229
Mrs. Medlock said unceremoniously:"Well, here you are!

540
00:29:20,229 --> 00:29:22,839
This room and the next are where you'lllive--and you must keep to them.

541
00:29:22,839 --> 00:29:24,789
Don't you forget that!"

542
00:29:24,789 --> 00:29:29,033
It was in this way Mistress Mary arrived atMisselthwaite Manor and she had perhaps

543
00:29:29,033 --> 00:29:36,025
never felt quite so contrary in all herlife.

544
00:29:36,025 --> 00:29:37,025
>

545
00:29:37,025 --> 00:29:44,091
CHAPTER IVMARTHA

546
00:29:44,091 --> 00:29:48,079
When she opened her eyes in the morning itwas because a young housemaid had come into

547
00:29:48,079 --> 00:29:52,082
her room to light the fire and was kneelingon the hearth-rug raking out the cinders

548
00:29:52,082 --> 00:29:53,389
noisily.

549
00:29:53,389 --> 00:29:58,008
Mary lay and watched her for a few momentsand then began to look about the room.

550
00:29:58,008 --> 00:30:03,026
She had never seen a room at all like itand thought it curious and gloomy.

551
00:30:03,026 --> 00:30:06,289
The walls were covered with tapestry with aforest scene embroidered on it.

552
00:30:06,289 --> 00:30:10,023
There were fantastically dressed peopleunder the trees and in the distance there

553
00:30:10,023 --> 00:30:12,409
was a glimpse of the turrets of a castle.

554
00:30:12,409 --> 00:30:16,339
There were hunters and horses and dogs andladies.

555
00:30:16,339 --> 00:30:19,109
Mary felt as if she were in the forest withthem.

556
00:30:19,109 --> 00:30:22,078
Out of a deep window she could see a greatclimbing stretch of land which seemed to

557
00:30:22,078 --> 00:30:28,001
have no trees on it, and to look ratherlike an endless, dull, purplish sea.

558
00:30:28,001 --> 00:30:31,879
"What is that?" she said, pointing out ofthe window.

559
00:30:31,879 --> 00:30:36,299
Martha, the young housemaid, who had justrisen to her feet, looked and pointed also.

560
00:30:36,299 --> 00:30:37,179
"That there?" she said.

561
00:30:37,179 --> 00:30:39,929
"Yes.""That's th' moor," with a good-natured

562
00:30:39,929 --> 00:30:41,069
grin."Does tha' like it?"

563
00:30:41,069 --> 00:30:43,035
"No," answered Mary.

564
00:30:43,035 --> 00:30:46,007
"I hate it.""That's because tha'rt not used to it,"

565
00:30:46,007 --> 00:30:50,052
Martha said, going back to her hearth."Tha' thinks it's too big an' bare now.

566
00:30:50,052 --> 00:30:51,619
But tha' will like it."

567
00:30:51,619 --> 00:30:56,409
"Do you?" inquired Mary."Aye, that I do," answered Martha,

568
00:30:56,409 --> 00:30:59,439
cheerfully polishing away at the grate."I just love it.

569
00:30:59,439 --> 00:31:00,579
It's none bare.

570
00:31:00,579 --> 00:31:03,289
It's covered wi' growin' things as smellssweet.

571
00:31:03,289 --> 00:31:06,619
It's fair lovely in spring an' summer whenth' gorse an' broom an' heather's in

572
00:31:06,619 --> 00:31:07,549
flower.

573
00:31:07,549 --> 00:31:11,719
It smells o' honey an' there's such a loto' fresh air--an' th' sky looks so high an'

574
00:31:11,719 --> 00:31:15,119
th' bees an' skylarks makes such a nicenoise hummin' an' singin'.

575
00:31:15,119 --> 00:31:18,999
Eh! I wouldn't live away from th' moor foranythin'."

576
00:31:18,999 --> 00:31:22,014
Mary listened to her with a grave, puzzledexpression.

577
00:31:22,014 --> 00:31:25,109
The native servants she had been used to inIndia were not in the least like this.

578
00:31:25,109 --> 00:31:29,569
They were obsequious and servile and didnot presume to talk to their masters as if

579
00:31:29,569 --> 00:31:30,789
they were their equals.

580
00:31:30,789 --> 00:31:34,159
They made salaams and called them"protector of the poor" and names of that

581
00:31:34,159 --> 00:31:36,085
sort.Indian servants were commanded to do

582
00:31:36,085 --> 00:31:38,369
things, not asked.

583
00:31:38,369 --> 00:31:42,399
It was not the custom to say "please" and"thank you" and Mary had always slapped her

584
00:31:42,399 --> 00:31:46,056
Ayah in the face when she was angry.She wondered a little what this girl would

585
00:31:46,056 --> 00:31:48,319
do if one slapped her in the face.

586
00:31:48,319 --> 00:31:52,067
She was a round, rosy, good-natured-lookingcreature, but she had a sturdy way which

587
00:31:52,067 --> 00:31:56,086
made Mistress Mary wonder if she might noteven slap back--if the person who slapped

588
00:31:56,086 --> 00:31:59,014
her was only a little girl.

589
00:31:59,014 --> 00:32:02,051
"You are a strange servant," she said fromher pillows, rather haughtily.

590
00:32:02,051 --> 00:32:06,011
Martha sat up on her heels, with herblacking-brush in her hand, and laughed,

591
00:32:06,011 --> 00:32:07,959
without seeming the least out of temper.

592
00:32:07,959 --> 00:32:11,036
"Eh! I know that," she said."If there was a grand Missus at

593
00:32:11,036 --> 00:32:14,011
Misselthwaite I should never have been evenone of th' under house-maids.

594
00:32:14,011 --> 00:32:18,004
I might have been let to be scullerymaidbut I'd never have been let upstairs.

595
00:32:18,004 --> 00:32:20,072
I'm too common an' I talk too muchYorkshire.

596
00:32:20,072 --> 00:32:24,048
But this is a funny house for all it's sogrand.

597
00:32:24,048 --> 00:32:28,239
Seems like there's neither Master norMistress except Mr. Pitcher an' Mrs.

598
00:32:28,239 --> 00:32:28,065
Medlock.

599
00:32:28,065 --> 00:32:31,879
Mr. Craven, he won't be troubled aboutanythin' when he's here, an' he's nearly

600
00:32:31,879 --> 00:32:35,022
always away.Mrs. Medlock gave me th' place out o'

601
00:32:35,022 --> 00:32:35,489
kindness.

602
00:32:35,489 --> 00:32:38,089
She told me she could never have done it ifMisselthwaite had been like other big

603
00:32:38,089 --> 00:32:40,068
houses.""Are you going to be my servant?"

604
00:32:40,068 --> 00:32:43,159
Mary asked, still in her imperious littleIndian way.

605
00:32:43,159 --> 00:32:48,159
Martha began to rub her grate again."I'm Mrs. Medlock's servant," she said

606
00:32:48,159 --> 00:32:48,709
stoutly.

607
00:32:48,709 --> 00:32:52,076
"An' she's Mr. Craven's--but I'm to do thehousemaid's work up here an' wait on you a

608
00:32:52,076 --> 00:32:54,007
bit.But you won't need much waitin' on."

609
00:32:54,007 --> 00:32:57,989
"Who is going to dress me?" demanded Mary.

610
00:32:57,989 --> 00:33:00,037
Martha sat up on her heels again andstared.

611
00:33:00,037 --> 00:33:02,769
She spoke in broad Yorkshire in heramazement.

612
00:33:02,769 --> 00:33:04,849
"Canna' tha' dress thysen!" she said.

613
00:33:04,849 --> 00:33:08,025
"What do you mean?I don't understand your language," said

614
00:33:08,025 --> 00:33:11,719
Mary."Eh! I forgot," Martha said.

615
00:33:11,719 --> 00:33:14,075
"Mrs. Medlock told me I'd have to becareful or you wouldn't know what I was

616
00:33:14,075 --> 00:33:18,023
sayin'.I mean can't you put on your own clothes?"

617
00:33:18,023 --> 00:33:20,011
"No," answered Mary, quite indignantly.

618
00:33:20,011 --> 00:33:24,319
"I never did in my life.My Ayah dressed me, of course."

619
00:33:24,319 --> 00:33:28,009
"Well," said Martha, evidently not in theleast aware that she was impudent, "it's

620
00:33:28,009 --> 00:33:29,799
time tha' should learn.

621
00:33:29,799 --> 00:33:33,609
Tha' cannot begin younger.It'll do thee good to wait on thysen a bit.

622
00:33:33,609 --> 00:33:37,379
My mother always said she couldn't see whygrand people's children didn't turn out

623
00:33:37,379 --> 00:33:40,939
fair fools--what with nurses an' bein'washed an' dressed an' took out to walk as

624
00:33:40,939 --> 00:33:41,629
if they was puppies!"

625
00:33:41,629 --> 00:33:46,069
"It is different in India," said MistressMary disdainfully.

626
00:33:46,069 --> 00:33:49,489
She could scarcely stand this.But Martha was not at all crushed.

627
00:33:49,489 --> 00:33:52,609
"Eh! I can see it's different," sheanswered almost sympathetically.

628
00:33:52,609 --> 00:33:56,044
"I dare say it's because there's such a loto' blacks there instead o' respectable

629
00:33:56,044 --> 00:33:57,007
white people.

630
00:33:57,007 --> 00:34:01,056
When I heard you was comin' from India Ithought you was a black too."

631
00:34:01,056 --> 00:34:07,005
Mary sat up in bed furious."What!" she said.

632
00:34:07,005 --> 00:34:07,053
"What!

633
00:34:07,053 --> 00:34:11,077
You thought I was a native.You--you daughter of a pig!"

634
00:34:11,077 --> 00:34:16,024
Martha stared and looked hot."Who are you callin' names?" she said.

635
00:34:16,024 --> 00:34:17,044
"You needn't be so vexed.

636
00:34:17,044 --> 00:34:20,074
That's not th' way for a young lady totalk.

637
00:34:20,074 --> 00:34:23,054
I've nothin' against th' blacks.When you read about 'em in tracts they're

638
00:34:23,054 --> 00:34:25,008
always very religious.

639
00:34:25,008 --> 00:34:27,048
You always read as a black's a man an' abrother.

640
00:34:27,048 --> 00:34:31,019
I've never seen a black an' I was fairpleased to think I was goin' to see one

641
00:34:31,019 --> 00:34:31,033
close.

642
00:34:31,033 --> 00:34:34,028
When I come in to light your fire thismornin' I crep' up to your bed an' pulled

643
00:34:34,028 --> 00:34:36,088
th' cover back careful to look at you.

644
00:34:36,088 --> 00:34:41,048
An' there you was," disappointedly, "nomore black than me--for all you're so

645
00:34:41,048 --> 00:34:43,088
yeller."Mary did not even try to control her rage

646
00:34:43,088 --> 00:34:44,074
and humiliation.

647
00:34:44,074 --> 00:34:47,052
"You thought I was a native!You dared!

648
00:34:47,052 --> 00:34:52,023
You don't know anything about natives!They are not people--they're servants who

649
00:34:52,023 --> 00:34:53,044
must salaam to you.

650
00:34:53,044 --> 00:34:57,094
You know nothing about India.You know nothing about anything!"

651
00:34:57,094 --> 00:35:02,058
She was in such a rage and felt so helplessbefore the girl's simple stare, and somehow

652
00:35:02,058 --> 00:35:07,038
she suddenly felt so horribly lonely andfar away from everything she understood and

653
00:35:07,038 --> 00:35:09,031
which understood her, that she threw

654
00:35:09,031 --> 00:35:13,022
herself face downward on the pillows andburst into passionate sobbing.

655
00:35:13,022 --> 00:35:17,033
She sobbed so unrestrainedly that good-natured Yorkshire Martha was a little

656
00:35:17,033 --> 00:35:19,043
frightened and quite sorry for her.

657
00:35:19,043 --> 00:35:23,032
She went to the bed and bent over her."Eh! you mustn't cry like that there!" she

658
00:35:23,032 --> 00:35:25,002
begged."You mustn't for sure.

659
00:35:25,002 --> 00:35:26,042
I didn't know you'd be vexed.

660
00:35:26,042 --> 00:35:29,006
I don't know anythin' about anythin'--justlike you said.

661
00:35:29,006 --> 00:35:32,033
I beg your pardon, Miss.Do stop cryin'."

662
00:35:32,033 --> 00:35:36,043
There was something comforting and reallyfriendly in her queer Yorkshire speech and

663
00:35:36,043 --> 00:35:41,013
sturdy way which had a good effect on Mary.She gradually ceased crying and became

664
00:35:41,013 --> 00:35:41,055
quiet.

665
00:35:41,055 --> 00:35:45,055
Martha looked relieved."It's time for thee to get up now," she

666
00:35:45,055 --> 00:35:45,097
said.

667
00:35:45,097 --> 00:35:49,029
"Mrs. Medlock said I was to carry tha'breakfast an' tea an' dinner into th' room

668
00:35:49,029 --> 00:35:51,039
next to this.It's been made into a nursery for thee.

669
00:35:51,039 --> 00:35:54,063
I'll help thee on with thy clothes iftha'll get out o' bed.

670
00:35:54,063 --> 00:35:58,006
If th' buttons are at th' back tha' cannotbutton them up tha'self."

671
00:35:58,006 --> 00:36:02,021
When Mary at last decided to get up, theclothes Martha took from the wardrobe were

672
00:36:02,021 --> 00:36:05,062
not the ones she had worn when she arrivedthe night before with Mrs. Medlock.

673
00:36:05,062 --> 00:36:07,031
"Those are not mine," she said.

674
00:36:07,031 --> 00:36:10,008
"Mine are black."She looked the thick white wool coat and

675
00:36:10,008 --> 00:36:15,022
dress over, and added with cool approval:"Those are nicer than mine."

676
00:36:15,022 --> 00:36:18,003
"These are th' ones tha' must put on,"Martha answered.

677
00:36:18,003 --> 00:36:20,077
"Mr. Craven ordered Mrs. Medlock to get 'emin London.

678
00:36:20,077 --> 00:36:24,047
He said 'I won't have a child dressed inblack wanderin' about like a lost soul,' he

679
00:36:24,047 --> 00:36:27,036
said.'It'd make the place sadder than it is.

680
00:36:27,036 --> 00:36:28,086
Put color on her.'

681
00:36:28,086 --> 00:36:32,024
Mother she said she knew what he meant.Mother always knows what a body means.

682
00:36:32,024 --> 00:36:36,007
She doesn't hold with black hersel'.""I hate black things," said Mary.

683
00:36:36,007 --> 00:36:38,095
The dressing process was one which taughtthem both something.

684
00:36:38,095 --> 00:36:43,058
Martha had "buttoned up" her little sistersand brothers but she had never seen a child

685
00:36:43,058 --> 00:36:47,018
who stood still and waited for anotherperson to do things for her as if she had

686
00:36:47,018 --> 00:36:49,016
neither hands nor feet of her own.

687
00:36:49,016 --> 00:36:53,072
"Why doesn't tha' put on tha' own shoes?"she said when Mary quietly held out her

688
00:36:53,072 --> 00:36:56,021
foot."My Ayah did it," answered Mary, staring.

689
00:36:56,021 --> 00:36:58,024
"It was the custom."

690
00:36:58,024 --> 00:37:01,004
She said that very often--"It was thecustom."

691
00:37:01,004 --> 00:37:02,096
The native servants were always saying it.

692
00:37:02,096 --> 00:37:06,064
If one told them to do a thing theirancestors had not done for a thousand years

693
00:37:06,064 --> 00:37:10,099
they gazed at one mildly and said, "It isnot the custom" and one knew that was the

694
00:37:10,099 --> 00:37:12,037
end of the matter.

695
00:37:12,037 --> 00:37:15,051
It had not been the custom that MistressMary should do anything but stand and allow

696
00:37:15,051 --> 00:37:18,089
herself to be dressed like a doll, butbefore she was ready for breakfast she

697
00:37:18,089 --> 00:37:20,038
began to suspect that her life at

698
00:37:20,038 --> 00:37:24,053
Misselthwaite Manor would end by teachingher a number of things quite new to her--

699
00:37:24,053 --> 00:37:28,034
things such as putting on her own shoes andstockings, and picking up things she let

700
00:37:28,034 --> 00:37:29,024
fall.

701
00:37:29,024 --> 00:37:32,099
If Martha had been a well-trained fineyoung lady's maid she would have been more

702
00:37:32,099 --> 00:37:36,034
subservient and respectful and would haveknown that it was her business to brush

703
00:37:36,034 --> 00:37:39,071
hair, and button boots, and pick things upand lay them away.

704
00:37:39,071 --> 00:37:43,009
She was, however, only an untrainedYorkshire rustic who had been brought up in

705
00:37:43,009 --> 00:37:47,057
a moorland cottage with a swarm of littlebrothers and sisters who had never dreamed

706
00:37:47,057 --> 00:37:49,052
of doing anything but waiting on themselves

707
00:37:49,052 --> 00:37:53,014
and on the younger ones who were eitherbabies in arms or just learning to totter

708
00:37:53,014 --> 00:37:54,096
about and tumble over things.

709
00:37:54,096 --> 00:37:59,077
If Mary Lennox had been a child who wasready to be amused she would perhaps have

710
00:37:59,077 --> 00:38:04,011
laughed at Martha's readiness to talk, butMary only listened to her coldly and

711
00:38:04,011 --> 00:38:06,018
wondered at her freedom of manner.

712
00:38:06,018 --> 00:38:10,529
At first she was not at all interested, butgradually, as the girl rattled on in her

713
00:38:10,529 --> 00:38:14,229
good-tempered, homely way, Mary began tonotice what she was saying.

714
00:38:14,229 --> 00:38:16,024
"Eh! you should see 'em all," she said.

715
00:38:16,024 --> 00:38:20,005
"There's twelve of us an' my father onlygets sixteen shilling a week.

716
00:38:20,005 --> 00:38:23,089
I can tell you my mother's put to it to getporridge for 'em all.

717
00:38:23,089 --> 00:38:26,509
They tumble about on th' moor an' playthere all day an' mother says th' air of

718
00:38:26,509 --> 00:38:29,339
th' moor fattens 'em.She says she believes they eat th' grass

719
00:38:29,339 --> 00:38:31,089
same as th' wild ponies do.

720
00:38:31,089 --> 00:38:34,081
Our Dickon, he's twelve years old and he'sgot a young pony he calls his own."

721
00:38:34,081 --> 00:38:37,022
"Where did he get it?" asked Mary.

722
00:38:37,022 --> 00:38:40,016
"He found it on th' moor with its motherwhen it was a little one an' he began to

723
00:38:40,016 --> 00:38:43,769
make friends with it an' give it bits o'bread an' pluck young grass for it.

724
00:38:43,769 --> 00:38:49,041
And it got to like him so it follows himabout an' it lets him get on its back.

725
00:38:49,041 --> 00:38:50,629
Dickon's a kind lad an' animals likes him."

726
00:38:50,629 --> 00:38:54,209
Mary had never possessed an animal pet ofher own and had always thought she should

727
00:38:54,209 --> 00:38:54,099
like one.

728
00:38:54,099 --> 00:38:59,023
So she began to feel a slight interest inDickon, and as she had never before been

729
00:38:59,023 --> 00:39:04,037
interested in any one but herself, it wasthe dawning of a healthy sentiment.

730
00:39:04,037 --> 00:39:07,073
When she went into the room which had beenmade into a nursery for her, she found that

731
00:39:07,073 --> 00:39:09,529
it was rather like the one she had sleptin.

732
00:39:09,529 --> 00:39:14,012
It was not a child's room, but a grown-upperson's room, with gloomy old pictures on

733
00:39:14,012 --> 00:39:18,056
the walls and heavy old oak chairs.A table in the center was set with a good

734
00:39:18,056 --> 00:39:19,699
substantial breakfast.

735
00:39:19,699 --> 00:39:23,006
But she had always had a very smallappetite, and she looked with something

736
00:39:23,006 --> 00:39:26,899
more than indifference at the first plateMartha set before her.

737
00:39:26,899 --> 00:39:28,067
"I don't want it," she said.

738
00:39:28,067 --> 00:39:32,079
"Tha' doesn't want thy porridge!"Martha exclaimed incredulously.

739
00:39:32,079 --> 00:39:35,004
"No.""Tha' doesn't know how good it is.

740
00:39:35,004 --> 00:39:37,899
Put a bit o' treacle on it or a bit o'sugar."

741
00:39:37,899 --> 00:39:41,072
"I don't want it," repeated Mary."Eh!" said Martha.

742
00:39:41,072 --> 00:39:44,699
"I can't abide to see good victuals go towaste.

743
00:39:44,699 --> 00:39:48,041
If our children was at this table they'dclean it bare in five minutes."

744
00:39:48,041 --> 00:39:50,048
"Why?" said Mary coldly.

745
00:39:50,048 --> 00:39:53,999
"Why!" echoed Martha."Because they scarce ever had their

746
00:39:53,999 --> 00:39:57,022
stomachs full in their lives.They're as hungry as young hawks an'

747
00:39:57,022 --> 00:39:58,056
foxes."

748
00:39:58,056 --> 00:40:02,036
"I don't know what it is to be hungry,"said Mary, with the indifference of

749
00:40:02,036 --> 00:40:03,066
ignorance.Martha looked indignant.

750
00:40:03,066 --> 00:40:06,499
"Well, it would do thee good to try it.

751
00:40:06,499 --> 00:40:08,749
I can see that plain enough," she saidoutspokenly.

752
00:40:08,749 --> 00:40:12,072
"I've no patience with folk as sits an'just stares at good bread an' meat.

753
00:40:12,072 --> 00:40:17,149
My word! don't I wish Dickon and Phil an'Jane an' th' rest of 'em had what's here

754
00:40:17,149 --> 00:40:20,037
under their pinafores.""Why don't you take it to them?" suggested

755
00:40:20,037 --> 00:40:20,899
Mary.

756
00:40:20,899 --> 00:40:25,043
"It's not mine," answered Martha stoutly."An' this isn't my day out.

757
00:40:25,043 --> 00:40:27,092
I get my day out once a month same as th'rest.

758
00:40:27,092 --> 00:40:31,829
Then I go home an' clean up for mother an'give her a day's rest."

759
00:40:31,829 --> 00:40:35,259
Mary drank some tea and ate a little toastand some marmalade.

760
00:40:35,259 --> 00:40:37,939
"You wrap up warm an' run out an' playyou," said Martha.

761
00:40:37,939 --> 00:40:41,029
"It'll do you good and give you somestomach for your meat."

762
00:40:41,029 --> 00:40:42,459
Mary went to the window.

763
00:40:42,459 --> 00:40:47,062
There were gardens and paths and big trees,but everything looked dull and wintry.

764
00:40:47,062 --> 00:40:50,081
"Out? Why should I go out on a day likethis?"

765
00:40:50,081 --> 00:40:53,097
"Well, if tha' doesn't go out tha'lt haveto stay in, an' what has tha' got to do?"

766
00:40:53,097 --> 00:40:58,018
Mary glanced about her.There was nothing to do.

767
00:40:58,018 --> 00:41:02,649
When Mrs. Medlock had prepared the nurseryshe had not thought of amusement.

768
00:41:02,649 --> 00:41:05,099
Perhaps it would be better to go and seewhat the gardens were like.

769
00:41:05,099 --> 00:41:07,519
"Who will go with me?" she inquired.

770
00:41:07,519 --> 00:41:10,092
Martha stared."You'll go by yourself," she answered.

771
00:41:10,092 --> 00:41:14,017
"You'll have to learn to play like otherchildren does when they haven't got sisters

772
00:41:14,017 --> 00:41:15,016
and brothers.

773
00:41:15,016 --> 00:41:17,769
Our Dickon goes off on th' moor by himselfan' plays for hours.

774
00:41:17,769 --> 00:41:20,089
That's how he made friends with th' pony.

775
00:41:20,089 --> 00:41:23,319
He's got sheep on th' moor that knows him,an' birds as comes an' eats out of his

776
00:41:23,319 --> 00:41:25,949
hand.However little there is to eat, he always

777
00:41:25,949 --> 00:41:27,067
saves a bit o' his bread to coax his pets."

778
00:41:27,067 --> 00:41:33,005
It was really this mention of Dickon whichmade Mary decide to go out, though she was

779
00:41:33,005 --> 00:41:36,319
not aware of it.There would be, birds outside though there

780
00:41:36,319 --> 00:41:37,959
would not be ponies or sheep.

781
00:41:37,959 --> 00:41:42,649
They would be different from the birds inIndia and it might amuse her to look at

782
00:41:42,649 --> 00:41:43,029
them.

783
00:41:43,029 --> 00:41:46,008
Martha found her coat and hat for her and apair of stout little boots and she showed

784
00:41:46,008 --> 00:41:48,029
her her way downstairs.

785
00:41:48,029 --> 00:41:53,129
"If tha' goes round that way tha'll come toth' gardens," she said, pointing to a gate

786
00:41:53,129 --> 00:41:55,959
in a wall of shrubbery."There's lots o' flowers in summer-time,

787
00:41:55,959 --> 00:41:57,087
but there's nothin' bloomin' now."

788
00:41:57,087 --> 00:42:02,055
She seemed to hesitate a second before sheadded, "One of th' gardens is locked up.

789
00:42:02,055 --> 00:42:07,003
No one has been in it for ten years.""Why?" asked Mary in spite of herself.

790
00:42:07,003 --> 00:42:11,129
Here was another locked door added to thehundred in the strange house.

791
00:42:11,129 --> 00:42:14,017
"Mr. Craven had it shut when his wife diedso sudden.

792
00:42:14,017 --> 00:42:15,098
He won't let no one go inside.

793
00:42:15,098 --> 00:42:19,529
It was her garden.He locked th' door an' dug a hole and

794
00:42:19,529 --> 00:42:22,199
buried th' key.There's Mrs. Medlock's bell ringing--I must

795
00:42:22,199 --> 00:42:22,319
run."

796
00:42:22,319 --> 00:42:27,389
After she was gone Mary turned down thewalk which led to the door in the

797
00:42:27,389 --> 00:42:27,809
shrubbery.

798
00:42:27,809 --> 00:42:31,043
She could not help thinking about thegarden which no one had been into for ten

799
00:42:31,043 --> 00:42:31,899
years.

800
00:42:31,899 --> 00:42:35,072
She wondered what it would look like andwhether there were any flowers still alive

801
00:42:35,072 --> 00:42:36,319
in it.

802
00:42:36,319 --> 00:42:40,059
When she had passed through the shrubberygate she found herself in great gardens,

803
00:42:40,059 --> 00:42:42,091
with wide lawns and winding walks withclipped borders.

804
00:42:42,091 --> 00:42:47,749
There were trees, and flower-beds, andevergreens clipped into strange shapes, and

805
00:42:47,749 --> 00:42:50,639
a large pool with an old gray fountain inits midst.

806
00:42:50,639 --> 00:42:54,093
But the flower-beds were bare and wintryand the fountain was not playing.

807
00:42:54,093 --> 00:42:59,199
This was not the garden which was shut up.How could a garden be shut up?

808
00:42:59,199 --> 00:43:01,087
You could always walk into a garden.

809
00:43:01,087 --> 00:43:04,949
She was just thinking this when she sawthat, at the end of the path she was

810
00:43:04,949 --> 00:43:09,209
following, there seemed to be a long wall,with ivy growing over it.

811
00:43:09,209 --> 00:43:12,769
She was not familiar enough with England toknow that she was coming upon the kitchen-

812
00:43:12,769 --> 00:43:15,249
gardens where the vegetables and fruit weregrowing.

813
00:43:15,249 --> 00:43:18,749
She went toward the wall and found thatthere was a green door in the ivy, and that

814
00:43:18,749 --> 00:43:22,259
it stood open.This was not the closed garden, evidently,

815
00:43:22,259 --> 00:43:23,879
and she could go into it.

816
00:43:23,879 --> 00:43:27,439
She went through the door and found that itwas a garden with walls all round it and

817
00:43:27,439 --> 00:43:31,589
that it was only one of several walledgardens which seemed to open into one

818
00:43:31,589 --> 00:43:32,003
another.

819
00:43:32,003 --> 00:43:35,939
She saw another open green door, revealingbushes and pathways between beds containing

820
00:43:35,939 --> 00:43:37,449
winter vegetables.

821
00:43:37,449 --> 00:43:41,879
Fruit-trees were trained flat against thewall, and over some of the beds there were

822
00:43:41,879 --> 00:43:44,459
glass frames.The place was bare and ugly enough, Mary

823
00:43:44,459 --> 00:43:46,769
thought, as she stood and stared about her.

824
00:43:46,769 --> 00:43:50,069
It might be nicer in summer when thingswere green, but there was nothing pretty

825
00:43:50,069 --> 00:43:52,059
about it now.

826
00:43:52,059 --> 00:43:55,439
Presently an old man with a spade over hisshoulder walked through the door leading

827
00:43:55,439 --> 00:43:58,699
from the second garden.He looked startled when he saw Mary, and

828
00:43:58,699 --> 00:44:00,003
then touched his cap.

829
00:44:00,003 --> 00:44:04,619
He had a surly old face, and did not seemat all pleased to see her--but then she was

830
00:44:04,619 --> 00:44:08,569
displeased with his garden and wore her"quite contrary" expression, and certainly

831
00:44:08,569 --> 00:44:10,869
did not seem at all pleased to see him.

832
00:44:10,869 --> 00:44:15,054
"What is this place?" she asked."One o' th' kitchen-gardens," he answered.

833
00:44:15,054 --> 00:44:18,499
"What is that?" said Mary, pointing throughthe other green door.

834
00:44:18,499 --> 00:44:20,022
"Another of 'em," shortly.

835
00:44:20,022 --> 00:44:23,067
"There's another on t'other side o' th'wall an' there's th' orchard t'other side

836
00:44:23,067 --> 00:44:26,309
o' that.""Can I go in them?" asked Mary.

837
00:44:26,309 --> 00:44:27,055
"If tha' likes.

838
00:44:27,055 --> 00:44:31,529
But there's nowt to see."Mary made no response.

839
00:44:31,529 --> 00:44:33,649
She went down the path and through thesecond green door.

840
00:44:33,649 --> 00:44:38,016
There, she found more walls and wintervegetables and glass frames, but in the

841
00:44:38,016 --> 00:44:41,509
second wall there was another green doorand it was not open.

842
00:44:41,509 --> 00:44:44,569
Perhaps it led into the garden which no onehad seen for ten years.

843
00:44:44,569 --> 00:44:49,069
As she was not at all a timid child andalways did what she wanted to do, Mary went

844
00:44:49,069 --> 00:44:51,129
to the green door and turned the handle.

845
00:44:51,129 --> 00:44:54,019
She hoped the door would not open becauseshe wanted to be sure she had found the

846
00:44:54,019 --> 00:44:58,003
mysterious garden--but it did open quiteeasily and she walked through it and found

847
00:44:58,003 --> 00:44:59,569
herself in an orchard.

848
00:44:59,569 --> 00:45:04,379
There were walls all round it also andtrees trained against them, and there were

849
00:45:04,379 --> 00:45:07,819
bare fruit-trees growing in the winter-browned grass--but there was no green door

850
00:45:07,819 --> 00:45:08,099
to be seen anywhere.

851
00:45:08,099 --> 00:45:13,016
Mary looked for it, and yet when she hadentered the upper end of the garden she had

852
00:45:13,016 --> 00:45:16,999
noticed that the wall did not seem to endwith the orchard but to extend beyond it as

853
00:45:16,999 --> 00:45:19,061
if it enclosed a place at the other side.

854
00:45:19,061 --> 00:45:23,054
She could see the tops of trees above thewall, and when she stood still she saw a

855
00:45:23,054 --> 00:45:27,047
bird with a bright red breast sitting onthe topmost branch of one of them, and

856
00:45:27,047 --> 00:45:29,559
suddenly he burst into his winter song--

857
00:45:29,559 --> 00:45:32,819
almost as if he had caught sight of her andwas calling to her.

858
00:45:32,819 --> 00:45:37,089
She stopped and listened to him and somehowhis cheerful, friendly little whistle gave

859
00:45:37,089 --> 00:45:41,639
her a pleased feeling--even a disagreeablelittle girl may be lonely, and the big

860
00:45:41,639 --> 00:45:45,001
closed house and big bare moor and big bare

861
00:45:45,001 --> 00:45:49,439
gardens had made this one feel as if therewas no one left in the world but herself.

862
00:45:49,439 --> 00:45:52,073
If she had been an affectionate child, whohad been used to being loved, she would

863
00:45:52,073 --> 00:45:57,259
have broken her heart, but even though shewas "Mistress Mary Quite Contrary" she was

864
00:45:57,259 --> 00:45:59,199
desolate, and the bright-breasted little

865
00:45:59,199 --> 00:46:03,072
bird brought a look into her sour littleface which was almost a smile.

866
00:46:03,072 --> 00:46:05,889
She listened to him until he flew away.

867
00:46:05,889 --> 00:46:10,001
He was not like an Indian bird and sheliked him and wondered if she should ever

868
00:46:10,001 --> 00:46:13,679
see him again.Perhaps he lived in the mysterious garden

869
00:46:13,679 --> 00:46:15,449
and knew all about it.

870
00:46:15,449 --> 00:46:18,689
Perhaps it was because she had nothingwhatever to do that she thought so much of

871
00:46:18,689 --> 00:46:21,092
the deserted garden.She was curious about it and wanted to see

872
00:46:21,092 --> 00:46:23,309
what it was like.

873
00:46:23,309 --> 00:46:26,429
Why had Mr. Archibald Craven buried thekey?

874
00:46:26,429 --> 00:46:30,016
If he had liked his wife so much why did hehate her garden?

875
00:46:30,016 --> 00:46:33,047
She wondered if she should ever see him,but she knew that if she did she should not

876
00:46:33,047 --> 00:46:37,061
like him, and he would not like her, andthat she should only stand and stare at him

877
00:46:37,061 --> 00:46:39,022
and say nothing, though she should be

878
00:46:39,022 --> 00:46:42,088
wanting dreadfully to ask him why he haddone such a queer thing.

879
00:46:42,088 --> 00:46:45,094
"People never like me and I never likepeople," she thought.

880
00:46:45,094 --> 00:46:48,065
"And I never can talk as the Crawfordchildren could.

881
00:46:48,065 --> 00:46:52,064
They were always talking and laughing andmaking noises."

882
00:46:52,064 --> 00:46:56,038
She thought of the robin and of the way heseemed to sing his song at her, and as she

883
00:46:56,038 --> 00:47:00,026
remembered the tree-top he perched on shestopped rather suddenly on the path.

884
00:47:00,026 --> 00:47:06,057
"I believe that tree was in the secretgarden--I feel sure it was," she said.

885
00:47:06,057 --> 00:47:09,074
"There was a wall round the place and therewas no door."

886
00:47:09,074 --> 00:47:13,037
She walked back into the first kitchen-garden she had entered and found the old

887
00:47:13,037 --> 00:47:16,052
man digging there.She went and stood beside him and watched

888
00:47:16,052 --> 00:47:18,069
him a few moments in her cold little way.

889
00:47:18,069 --> 00:47:22,014
He took no notice of her and so at last shespoke to him.

890
00:47:22,014 --> 00:47:24,028
"I have been into the other gardens," shesaid.

891
00:47:24,028 --> 00:47:27,004
"There was nothin' to prevent thee," heanswered crustily.

892
00:47:27,004 --> 00:47:30,081
"I went into the orchard.""There was no dog at th' door to bite

893
00:47:30,081 --> 00:47:31,008
thee," he answered.

894
00:47:31,008 --> 00:47:36,000
"There was no door there into the othergarden," said Mary.

895
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:40,018
"What garden?" he said in a rough voice,stopping his digging for a moment.

896
00:47:40,018 --> 00:47:42,086
"The one on the other side of the wall,"answered Mistress Mary.

897
00:47:42,086 --> 00:47:45,009
"There are trees there--I saw the tops ofthem.

898
00:47:45,009 --> 00:47:49,032
A bird with a red breast was sitting on oneof them and he sang."

899
00:47:49,032 --> 00:47:53,021
To her surprise the surly old weather-beaten face actually changed its

900
00:47:53,021 --> 00:47:54,036
expression.

901
00:47:54,036 --> 00:47:58,021
A slow smile spread over it and thegardener looked quite different.

902
00:47:58,021 --> 00:48:02,044
It made her think that it was curious howmuch nicer a person looked when he smiled.

903
00:48:02,044 --> 00:48:04,054
She had not thought of it before.

904
00:48:04,054 --> 00:48:09,001
He turned about to the orchard side of hisgarden and began to whistle--a low soft

905
00:48:09,001 --> 00:48:11,092
whistle.She could not understand how such a surly

906
00:48:11,092 --> 00:48:14,079
man could make such a coaxing sound.

907
00:48:14,079 --> 00:48:17,004
Almost the next moment a wonderful thinghappened.

908
00:48:17,004 --> 00:48:20,087
She heard a soft little rushing flightthrough the air--and it was the bird with

909
00:48:20,087 --> 00:48:25,015
the red breast flying to them, and heactually alighted on the big clod of earth

910
00:48:25,015 --> 00:48:26,075
quite near to the gardener's foot.

911
00:48:26,075 --> 00:48:30,079
"Here he is," chuckled the old man, andthen he spoke to the bird as if he were

912
00:48:30,079 --> 00:48:34,027
speaking to a child."Where has tha' been, tha' cheeky little

913
00:48:34,027 --> 00:48:34,009
beggar?" he said.

914
00:48:34,009 --> 00:48:39,005
"I've not seen thee before today.Has tha, begun tha' courtin' this early in

915
00:48:39,005 --> 00:48:40,035
th' season?Tha'rt too forrad."

916
00:48:40,035 --> 00:48:45,044
The bird put his tiny head on one side andlooked up at him with his soft bright eye

917
00:48:45,044 --> 00:48:49,071
which was like a black dewdrop.He seemed quite familiar and not the least

918
00:48:49,071 --> 00:48:50,071
afraid.

919
00:48:50,071 --> 00:48:54,054
He hopped about and pecked the earthbriskly, looking for seeds and insects.

920
00:48:54,054 --> 00:48:59,033
It actually gave Mary a queer feeling inher heart, because he was so pretty and

921
00:48:59,033 --> 00:49:02,013
cheerful and seemed so like a person.

922
00:49:02,013 --> 00:49:05,059
He had a tiny plump body and a delicatebeak, and slender delicate legs.

923
00:49:05,059 --> 00:49:10,057
"Will he always come when you call him?"she asked almost in a whisper.

924
00:49:10,057 --> 00:49:12,035
"Aye, that he will.

925
00:49:12,035 --> 00:49:14,056
I've knowed him ever since he was afledgling.

926
00:49:14,056 --> 00:49:18,004
He come out of th' nest in th' other gardenan' when first he flew over th' wall he was

927
00:49:18,004 --> 00:49:21,013
too weak to fly back for a few days an' wegot friendly.

928
00:49:21,013 --> 00:49:24,038
When he went over th' wall again th' restof th' brood was gone an' he was lonely an'

929
00:49:24,038 --> 00:49:27,029
he come back to me.""What kind of a bird is he?"

930
00:49:27,029 --> 00:49:28,032
Mary asked.

931
00:49:28,032 --> 00:49:31,098
"Doesn't tha' know?He's a robin redbreast an' they're th'

932
00:49:31,098 --> 00:49:35,039
friendliest, curiousest birds alive.They're almost as friendly as dogs--if you

933
00:49:35,039 --> 00:49:36,079
know how to get on with 'em.

934
00:49:36,079 --> 00:49:39,083
Watch him peckin' about there an' lookin'round at us now an' again.

935
00:49:39,083 --> 00:49:43,078
He knows we're talkin' about him."It was the queerest thing in the world to

936
00:49:43,078 --> 00:49:44,082
see the old fellow.

937
00:49:44,082 --> 00:49:48,019
He looked at the plump little scarlet-waistcoated bird as if he were both proud

938
00:49:48,019 --> 00:49:51,026
and fond of him."He's a conceited one," he chuckled.

939
00:49:51,026 --> 00:49:53,039
"He likes to hear folk talk about him.

940
00:49:53,039 --> 00:49:57,081
An' curious--bless me, there never was hislike for curiosity an' meddlin'.

941
00:49:57,081 --> 00:50:00,001
He's always comin' to see what I'mplantin'.

942
00:50:00,001 --> 00:50:03,007
He knows all th' things Mester Craven nevertroubles hissel' to find out.

943
00:50:03,007 --> 00:50:05,075
He's th' head gardener, he is."

944
00:50:05,075 --> 00:50:10,022
The robin hopped about busily pecking thesoil and now and then stopped and looked at

945
00:50:10,022 --> 00:50:12,065
them a little.Mary thought his black dewdrop eyes gazed

946
00:50:12,065 --> 00:50:14,026
at her with great curiosity.

947
00:50:14,026 --> 00:50:17,072
It really seemed as if he were finding outall about her.

948
00:50:17,072 --> 00:50:21,099
The queer feeling in her heart increased."Where did the rest of the brood fly to?"

949
00:50:21,099 --> 00:50:22,068
she asked.

950
00:50:22,068 --> 00:50:25,045
"There's no knowin'.The old ones turn 'em out o' their nest an'

951
00:50:25,045 --> 00:50:28,039
make 'em fly an' they're scattered beforeyou know it.

952
00:50:28,039 --> 00:50:31,086
This one was a knowin' one an' he knew hewas lonely."

953
00:50:31,086 --> 00:50:35,053
Mistress Mary went a step nearer to therobin and looked at him very hard.

954
00:50:35,053 --> 00:50:37,056
"I'm lonely," she said.

955
00:50:37,056 --> 00:50:42,001
She had not known before that this was oneof the things which made her feel sour and

956
00:50:42,001 --> 00:50:43,093
cross.She seemed to find it out when the robin

957
00:50:43,093 --> 00:50:47,006
looked at her and she looked at the robin.

958
00:50:47,006 --> 00:50:51,056
The old gardener pushed his cap back on hisbald head and stared at her a minute.

959
00:50:51,056 --> 00:50:54,002
"Art tha' th' little wench from India?" heasked.

960
00:50:54,002 --> 00:50:55,006
Mary nodded.

961
00:50:55,006 --> 00:50:58,067
"Then no wonder tha'rt lonely.Tha'lt be lonlier before tha's done," he

962
00:50:58,067 --> 00:50:59,093
said.

963
00:50:59,093 --> 00:51:04,061
He began to dig again, driving his spadedeep into the rich black garden soil while

964
00:51:04,061 --> 00:51:07,008
the robin hopped about very busilyemployed.

965
00:51:07,008 --> 00:51:08,002
"What is your name?"

966
00:51:08,002 --> 00:51:10,079
Mary inquired.He stood up to answer her.

967
00:51:10,079 --> 00:51:15,027
"Ben Weatherstaff," he answered, and thenhe added with a surly chuckle, "I'm lonely

968
00:51:15,027 --> 00:51:19,007
mysel' except when he's with me," and hejerked his thumb toward the robin.

969
00:51:19,007 --> 00:51:20,008
"He's th' only friend I've got."

970
00:51:20,008 --> 00:51:24,015
"I have no friends at all," said Mary."I never had.

971
00:51:24,015 --> 00:51:26,037
My Ayah didn't like me and I never playedwith any one."

972
00:51:26,037 --> 00:51:31,054
It is a Yorkshire habit to say what youthink with blunt frankness, and old Ben

973
00:51:31,054 --> 00:51:35,091
Weatherstaff was a Yorkshire moor man."Tha' an' me are a good bit alike," he

974
00:51:35,091 --> 00:51:36,034
said.

975
00:51:36,034 --> 00:51:40,022
"We was wove out of th' same cloth.We're neither of us good lookin' an' we're

976
00:51:40,022 --> 00:51:43,082
both of us as sour as we look.We've got the same nasty tempers, both of

977
00:51:43,082 --> 00:51:45,015
us, I'll warrant."

978
00:51:45,015 --> 00:51:49,011
This was plain speaking, and Mary Lennoxhad never heard the truth about herself in

979
00:51:49,011 --> 00:51:51,073
her life.Native servants always salaamed and

980
00:51:51,073 --> 00:51:53,071
submitted to you, whatever you did.

981
00:51:53,071 --> 00:51:57,032
She had never thought much about her looks,but she wondered if she was as unattractive

982
00:51:57,032 --> 00:52:01,082
as Ben Weatherstaff and she also wonderedif she looked as sour as he had looked

983
00:52:01,082 --> 00:52:03,012
before the robin came.

984
00:52:03,012 --> 00:52:07,026
She actually began to wonder also if shewas "nasty tempered."

985
00:52:07,026 --> 00:52:11,007
She felt uncomfortable.Suddenly a clear rippling little sound

986
00:52:11,007 --> 00:52:14,012
broke out near her and she turned round.

987
00:52:14,012 --> 00:52:17,069
She was standing a few feet from a youngapple-tree and the robin had flown on to

988
00:52:17,069 --> 00:52:20,099
one of its branches and had burst out intoa scrap of a song.

989
00:52:20,099 --> 00:52:23,019
Ben Weatherstaff laughed outright.

990
00:52:23,019 --> 00:52:27,003
"What did he do that for?" asked Mary."He's made up his mind to make friends with

991
00:52:27,003 --> 00:52:30,007
thee," replied Ben."Dang me if he hasn't took a fancy to

992
00:52:30,007 --> 00:52:30,082
thee."

993
00:52:30,082 --> 00:52:36,002
"To me?" said Mary, and she moved towardthe little tree softly and looked up.

994
00:52:36,002 --> 00:52:39,044
"Would you make friends with me?" she saidto the robin just as if she was speaking to

995
00:52:39,044 --> 00:52:40,003
a person.

996
00:52:40,003 --> 00:52:41,004
"Would you?"

997
00:52:41,004 --> 00:52:45,019
And she did not say it either in her hardlittle voice or in her imperious Indian

998
00:52:45,019 --> 00:52:50,019
voice, but in a tone so soft and eager andcoaxing that Ben Weatherstaff was as

999
00:52:50,019 --> 00:52:53,026
surprised as she had been when she heardhim whistle.

1000
00:52:53,026 --> 00:52:57,091
"Why," he cried out, "tha' said that asnice an' human as if tha' was a real child

1001
00:52:57,091 --> 00:52:59,063
instead of a sharp old woman.

1002
00:52:59,063 --> 00:53:02,002
Tha' said it almost like Dickon talks tohis wild things on th' moor."

1003
00:53:02,002 --> 00:53:05,026
"Do you know Dickon?"Mary asked, turning round rather in a

1004
00:53:05,026 --> 00:53:06,097
hurry.

1005
00:53:06,097 --> 00:53:09,052
"Everybody knows him.Dickon's wanderin' about everywhere.

1006
00:53:09,052 --> 00:53:12,063
Th' very blackberries an' heather-bellsknows him.

1007
00:53:12,063 --> 00:53:16,051
I warrant th' foxes shows him where theircubs lies an' th' skylarks doesn't hide

1008
00:53:16,051 --> 00:53:19,004
their nests from him."Mary would have liked to ask some more

1009
00:53:19,004 --> 00:53:20,044
questions.

1010
00:53:20,044 --> 00:53:23,009
She was almost as curious about Dickon asshe was about the deserted garden.

1011
00:53:23,009 --> 00:53:27,088
But just that moment the robin, who hadended his song, gave a little shake of his

1012
00:53:27,088 --> 00:53:30,001
wings, spread them and flew away.

1013
00:53:30,001 --> 00:53:32,064
He had made his visit and had other thingsto do.

1014
00:53:32,064 --> 00:53:35,065
"He has flown over the wall!"Mary cried out, watching him.

1015
00:53:35,065 --> 00:53:38,007
"He has flown into the orchard--he hasflown across the other wall--into the

1016
00:53:38,007 --> 00:53:41,077
garden where there is no door!""He lives there," said old Ben.

1017
00:53:41,077 --> 00:53:43,052
"He came out o' th' egg there.

1018
00:53:43,052 --> 00:53:48,002
If he's courtin', he's makin' up to someyoung madam of a robin that lives among th'

1019
00:53:48,002 --> 00:53:51,000
old rose-trees there.""Rose-trees," said Mary.

1020
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:52,049
"Are there rose-trees?"

1021
00:53:52,049 --> 00:53:55,001
Ben Weatherstaff took up his spade againand began to dig.

1022
00:53:55,001 --> 00:53:59,051
"There was ten year' ago," he mumbled."I should like to see them," said Mary.

1023
00:53:59,051 --> 00:54:00,092
"Where is the green door?

1024
00:54:00,092 --> 00:54:05,082
There must be a door somewhere."Ben drove his spade deep and looked as

1025
00:54:05,082 --> 00:54:08,074
uncompanionable as he had looked when shefirst saw him.

1026
00:54:08,074 --> 00:54:11,061
"There was ten year' ago, but there isn'tnow," he said.

1027
00:54:11,061 --> 00:54:14,083
"No door!" cried Mary."There must be."

1028
00:54:14,083 --> 00:54:18,013
"None as any one can find, an' none as isany one's business.

1029
00:54:18,013 --> 00:54:21,013
Don't you be a meddlesome wench an' pokeyour nose where it's no cause to go.

1030
00:54:21,013 --> 00:54:23,039
Here, I must go on with my work.

1031
00:54:23,039 --> 00:54:25,083
Get you gone an' play you.I've no more time."

1032
00:54:25,083 --> 00:54:29,015
And he actually stopped digging, threw hisspade over his shoulder and walked off,

1033
00:54:29,015 --> 00:54:35,025
without even glancing at her or sayinggood-by.

1034
