1035
00:54:36,025 --> 00:54:43,029
CHAPTER VTHE CRY IN THE CORRIDOR

1036
00:54:43,029 --> 00:54:49,002
At first each day which passed by for MaryLennox was exactly like the others.

1037
00:54:49,002 --> 00:54:52,084
Every morning she awoke in her tapestriedroom and found Martha kneeling upon the

1038
00:54:52,084 --> 00:54:57,021
hearth building her fire; every morning sheate her breakfast in the nursery which had

1039
00:54:57,021 --> 00:54:59,034
nothing amusing in it; and after each

1040
00:54:59,034 --> 00:55:03,038
breakfast she gazed out of the windowacross to the huge moor which seemed to

1041
00:55:03,038 --> 00:55:08,109
spread out on all sides and climb up to thesky, and after she had stared for a while

1042
00:55:08,109 --> 00:55:10,129
she realized that if she did not go out she

1043
00:55:10,129 --> 00:55:13,879
would have to stay in and do nothing--andso she went out.

1044
00:55:13,879 --> 00:55:17,025
She did not know that this was the bestthing she could have done, and she did not

1045
00:55:17,025 --> 00:55:21,589
know that, when she began to walk quicklyor even run along the paths and down the

1046
00:55:21,589 --> 00:55:24,008
avenue, she was stirring her slow blood and

1047
00:55:24,008 --> 00:55:28,028
making herself stronger by fighting withthe wind which swept down from the moor.

1048
00:55:28,028 --> 00:55:33,028
She ran only to make herself warm, and shehated the wind which rushed at her face and

1049
00:55:33,028 --> 00:55:37,022
roared and held her back as if it were somegiant she could not see.

1050
00:55:37,022 --> 00:55:41,005
But the big breaths of rough fresh airblown over the heather filled her lungs

1051
00:55:41,005 --> 00:55:46,011
with something which was good for her wholethin body and whipped some red color into

1052
00:55:46,011 --> 00:55:49,053
her cheeks and brightened her dull eyeswhen she did not know anything about it.

1053
00:55:49,053 --> 00:55:54,056
But after a few days spent almost entirelyout of doors she wakened one morning

1054
00:55:54,056 --> 00:55:58,004
knowing what it was to be hungry, and whenshe sat down to her breakfast she did not

1055
00:55:58,004 --> 00:56:00,009
glance disdainfully at her porridge and

1056
00:56:00,009 --> 00:56:04,018
push it away, but took up her spoon andbegan to eat it and went on eating it until

1057
00:56:04,018 --> 00:56:07,014
her bowl was empty."Tha' got on well enough with that this

1058
00:56:07,014 --> 00:56:09,022
mornin', didn't tha'?" said Martha.

1059
00:56:09,022 --> 00:56:12,077
"It tastes nice today," said Mary, feelinga little surprised her self.

1060
00:56:12,077 --> 00:56:16,003
"It's th' air of th' moor that's givin'thee stomach for tha' victuals," answered

1061
00:56:16,003 --> 00:56:16,051
Martha.

1062
00:56:16,051 --> 00:56:19,059
"It's lucky for thee that tha's gotvictuals as well as appetite.

1063
00:56:19,059 --> 00:56:23,035
There's been twelve in our cottage as hadth' stomach an' nothin' to put in it.

1064
00:56:23,035 --> 00:56:26,053
You go on playin' you out o' doors everyday an' you'll get some flesh on your bones

1065
00:56:26,053 --> 00:56:29,549
an' you won't be so yeller.""I don't play," said Mary.

1066
00:56:29,549 --> 00:56:31,027
"I have nothing to play with."

1067
00:56:31,027 --> 00:56:36,042
"Nothin' to play with!" exclaimed Martha."Our children plays with sticks and stones.

1068
00:56:36,042 --> 00:56:39,059
They just runs about an' shouts an' looksat things."

1069
00:56:39,059 --> 00:56:41,081
Mary did not shout, but she looked atthings.

1070
00:56:41,081 --> 00:56:45,599
There was nothing else to do.She walked round and round the gardens and

1071
00:56:45,599 --> 00:56:47,064
wandered about the paths in the park.

1072
00:56:47,064 --> 00:56:51,043
Sometimes she looked for Ben Weatherstaff,but though several times she saw him at

1073
00:56:51,043 --> 00:56:54,009
work he was too busy to look at her or wastoo surly.

1074
00:56:54,009 --> 00:56:57,999
Once when she was walking toward him hepicked up his spade and turned away as if

1075
00:56:57,999 --> 00:57:01,939
he did it on purpose.One place she went to oftener than to any

1076
00:57:01,939 --> 00:57:02,065
other.

1077
00:57:02,065 --> 00:57:06,002
It was the long walk outside the gardenswith the walls round them.

1078
00:57:06,002 --> 00:57:10,249
There were bare flower-beds on either sideof it and against the walls ivy grew

1079
00:57:10,249 --> 00:57:11,004
thickly.

1080
00:57:11,004 --> 00:57:15,519
There was one part of the wall where thecreeping dark green leaves were more bushy

1081
00:57:15,519 --> 00:57:18,719
than elsewhere.It seemed as if for a long time that part

1082
00:57:18,719 --> 00:57:20,069
had been neglected.

1083
00:57:20,069 --> 00:57:23,889
The rest of it had been clipped and made tolook neat, but at this lower end of the

1084
00:57:23,889 --> 00:57:26,012
walk it had not been trimmed at all.

1085
00:57:26,012 --> 00:57:30,029
A few days after she had talked to BenWeatherstaff, Mary stopped to notice this

1086
00:57:30,029 --> 00:57:32,049
and wondered why it was so.

1087
00:57:32,049 --> 00:57:36,459
She had just paused and was looking up at along spray of ivy swinging in the wind when

1088
00:57:36,459 --> 00:57:40,569
she saw a gleam of scarlet and heard abrilliant chirp, and there, on the top of

1089
00:57:40,569 --> 00:57:42,189
the wall, forward perched Ben

1090
00:57:42,189 --> 00:57:46,079
Weatherstaff's robin redbreast, tiltingforward to look at her with his small head

1091
00:57:46,079 --> 00:57:49,093
on one side."Oh!" she cried out, "is it you--is it

1092
00:57:49,093 --> 00:57:50,099
you?"

1093
00:57:50,099 --> 00:57:53,799
And it did not seem at all queer to herthat she spoke to him as if she were sure

1094
00:57:53,799 --> 00:57:56,098
that he would understand and answer her.He did answer.

1095
00:57:56,098 --> 00:58:00,018
He twittered and chirped and hopped alongthe wall as if he were telling her all

1096
00:58:00,018 --> 00:58:01,569
sorts of things.

1097
00:58:01,569 --> 00:58:04,809
It seemed to Mistress Mary as if sheunderstood him, too, though he was not

1098
00:58:04,809 --> 00:58:07,059
speaking in words.It was as if he said:

1099
00:58:07,059 --> 00:58:07,034
"Good morning!

1100
00:58:07,034 --> 00:58:10,319
Isn't the wind nice?Isn't the sun nice?

1101
00:58:10,319 --> 00:58:13,279
Isn't everything nice?Let us both chirp and hop and twitter.

1102
00:58:13,279 --> 00:58:14,139
Come on!

1103
00:58:14,139 --> 00:58:17,189
Come on!"Mary began to laugh, and as he hopped and

1104
00:58:17,189 --> 00:58:19,739
took little flights along the wall she ranafter him.

1105
00:58:19,739 --> 00:58:25,023
Poor little thin, sallow, ugly Mary--sheactually looked almost pretty for a moment.

1106
00:58:25,023 --> 00:58:26,279
"I like you!

1107
00:58:26,279 --> 00:58:30,087
I like you!" she cried out, pattering downthe walk; and she chirped and tried to

1108
00:58:30,087 --> 00:58:34,129
whistle, which last she did not know how todo in the least.

1109
00:58:34,129 --> 00:58:38,001
But the robin seemed to be quite satisfiedand chirped and whistled back at her.

1110
00:58:38,001 --> 00:58:41,709
At last he spread his wings and made adarting flight to the top of a tree, where

1111
00:58:41,709 --> 00:58:44,018
he perched and sang loudly.

1112
00:58:44,018 --> 00:58:46,087
That reminded Mary of the first time shehad seen him.

1113
00:58:46,087 --> 00:58:50,079
He had been swinging on a tree-top then andshe had been standing in the orchard.

1114
00:58:50,079 --> 00:58:54,035
Now she was on the other side of theorchard and standing in the path outside a

1115
00:58:54,035 --> 00:58:57,659
wall--much lower down--and there was thesame tree inside.

