"I wish the spring was here now," saidMary.

1983
01:48:18,379 --> 01:48:21,054
"I want to see all the things that grow inEngland."

1984
01:48:21,054 --> 01:48:24,329
She had finished her dinner and gone to herfavorite seat on the hearth-rug.

1985
01:48:24,329 --> 01:48:28,049
"I wish--I wish I had a little spade," shesaid.

1986
01:48:28,049 --> 01:48:31,999
"Whatever does tha' want a spade for?"asked Martha, laughing.

1987
01:48:31,999 --> 01:48:35,189
"Art tha' goin' to take to diggin'?I must tell mother that, too."

1988
01:48:35,189 --> 01:48:38,099
Mary looked at the fire and pondered alittle.

1989
01:48:38,099 --> 01:48:42,499
She must be careful if she meant to keepher secret kingdom.

1990
01:48:42,499 --> 01:48:47,004
She wasn't doing any harm, but if Mr.Craven found out about the open door he

1991
01:48:47,004 --> 01:48:50,959
would be fearfully angry and get a new keyand lock it up forevermore.

1992
01:48:50,959 --> 01:48:52,054
She really could not bear that.

1993
01:48:52,054 --> 01:48:58,259
"This is such a big lonely place," she saidslowly, as if she were turning matters over

1994
01:48:58,259 --> 01:49:01,085
in her mind."The house is lonely, and the park is

1995
01:49:01,085 --> 01:49:04,139
lonely, and the gardens are lonely.

1996
01:49:04,139 --> 01:49:08,099
So many places seem shut up.I never did many things in India, but there

1997
01:49:08,099 --> 01:49:13,008
were more people to look at--natives andsoldiers marching by--and sometimes bands

1998
01:49:13,008 --> 01:49:17,016
playing, and my Ayah told me stories.

1999
01:49:17,016 --> 01:49:20,049
There is no one to talk to here except youand Ben Weatherstaff.

2000
01:49:20,049 --> 01:49:24,899
And you have to do your work and BenWeatherstaff won't speak to me often.

2001
01:49:24,899 --> 01:49:29,047
I thought if I had a little spade I coulddig somewhere as he does, and I might make

2002
01:49:29,047 --> 01:49:32,037
a little garden if he would give me someseeds."

2003
01:49:32,037 --> 01:49:34,139
Martha's face quite lighted up.

2004
01:49:34,139 --> 01:49:38,022
"There now!" she exclaimed, "if that wasn'tone of th' things mother said.

2005
01:49:38,022 --> 01:49:42,199
She says, 'There's such a lot o' room inthat big place, why don't they give her a

2006
01:49:42,199 --> 01:49:46,019
bit for herself, even if she doesn't plantnothin' but parsley an' radishes?

2007
01:49:46,019 --> 01:49:49,639
She'd dig an' rake away an' be right downhappy over it.'

2008
01:49:49,639 --> 01:49:53,061
Them was the very words she said.""Were they?" said Mary.

2009
01:49:53,061 --> 01:49:55,055
"How many things she knows, doesn't she?"

2010
01:49:55,055 --> 01:49:59,054
"Eh!" said Martha."It's like she says: 'A woman as brings up

2011
01:49:59,054 --> 01:50:02,709
twelve children learns something besidesher A B C.

2012
01:50:02,709 --> 01:50:06,699
Children's as good as 'rithmetic to set youfindin' out things.'"

2013
01:50:06,699 --> 01:50:09,047
"How much would a spade cost--a littleone?"

2014
01:50:09,047 --> 01:50:10,092
Mary asked.

2015
01:50:10,092 --> 01:50:15,073
"Well," was Martha's reflective answer, "atThwaite village there's a shop or so an' I

2016
01:50:15,073 --> 01:50:19,319
saw little garden sets with a spade an' arake an' a fork all tied together for two

2017
01:50:19,319 --> 01:50:19,829
shillings.

2018
01:50:19,829 --> 01:50:22,006
An' they was stout enough to work with,too."

2019
01:50:22,006 --> 01:50:25,819
"I've got more than that in my purse," saidMary.

2020
01:50:25,819 --> 01:50:29,099
"Mrs. Morrison gave me five shillings andMrs. Medlock gave me some money from Mr.

2021
01:50:29,099 --> 01:50:33,019
Craven.""Did he remember thee that much?" exclaimed

2022
01:50:33,019 --> 01:50:34,018
Martha.

2023
01:50:34,018 --> 01:50:36,085
"Mrs. Medlock said I was to have a shillinga week to spend.

2024
01:50:36,085 --> 01:50:39,074
She gives me one every Saturday.I didn't know what to spend it on."

2025
01:50:39,074 --> 01:50:42,003
"My word! that's riches," said Martha.

2026
01:50:42,003 --> 01:50:44,869
"Tha' can buy anything in th' world tha'wants.

2027
01:50:44,869 --> 01:50:49,029
Th' rent of our cottage is only one an'threepence an' it's like pullin' eye-teeth

2028
01:50:49,029 --> 01:50:50,319
to get it.

2029
01:50:50,319 --> 01:50:53,008
Now I've just thought of somethin',"putting her hands on her hips.

2030
01:50:53,008 --> 01:50:55,068
"What?" said Mary eagerly.

2031
01:50:55,068 --> 01:51:01,059
"In the shop at Thwaite they sell packageso' flower-seeds for a penny each, and our

2032
01:51:01,059 --> 01:51:04,819
Dickon he knows which is th' prettiest onesan' how to make 'em grow.

2033
01:51:04,819 --> 01:51:07,085
He walks over to Thwaite many a day justfor th' fun of it.

2034
01:51:07,085 --> 01:51:10,006
Does tha' know how to print letters?"suddenly.

2035
01:51:10,006 --> 01:51:12,006
"I know how to write," Mary answered.

2036
01:51:12,006 --> 01:51:16,016
Martha shook her head."Our Dickon can only read printin'.

2037
01:51:16,016 --> 01:51:20,029
If tha' could print we could write a letterto him an' ask him to go an' buy th' garden

2038
01:51:20,029 --> 01:51:22,759
tools an' th' seeds at th' same time."

2039
01:51:22,759 --> 01:51:25,129
"Oh! you're a good girl!"Mary cried.

2040
01:51:25,129 --> 01:51:28,079
"You are, really!I didn't know you were so nice.

2041
01:51:28,079 --> 01:51:30,016
I know I can print letters if I try.

2042
01:51:30,016 --> 01:51:33,079
Let's ask Mrs. Medlock for a pen and inkand some paper."

2043
01:51:33,079 --> 01:51:36,749
"I've got some of my own," said Martha."I bought 'em so I could print a bit of a

2044
01:51:36,749 --> 01:51:37,098
letter to mother of a Sunday.

2045
01:51:37,098 --> 01:51:41,879
I'll go and get it."She ran out of the room, and Mary stood by

2046
01:51:41,879 --> 01:51:45,016
the fire and twisted her thin little handstogether with sheer pleasure.

2047
01:51:45,016 --> 01:51:50,619
"If I have a spade," she whispered, "I canmake the earth nice and soft and dig up

2048
01:51:50,619 --> 01:51:51,209
weeds.

2049
01:51:51,209 --> 01:51:55,139
If I have seeds and can make flowers growthe garden won't be dead at all--it will

2050
01:51:55,139 --> 01:51:57,042
come alive."

2051
01:51:57,042 --> 01:52:01,009
She did not go out again that afternoonbecause when Martha returned with her pen

2052
01:52:01,009 --> 01:52:04,098
and ink and paper she was obliged to clearthe table and carry the plates and dishes

2053
01:52:04,098 --> 01:52:06,091
downstairs and when she got into the

2054
01:52:06,091 --> 01:52:11,029
kitchen Mrs. Medlock was there and told herto do something, so Mary waited for what

2055
01:52:11,029 --> 01:52:14,179
seemed to her a long time before she cameback.

2056
01:52:14,179 --> 01:52:17,047
Then it was a serious piece of work towrite to Dickon.

2057
01:52:17,047 --> 01:52:20,098
Mary had been taught very little becauseher governesses had disliked her too much

2058
01:52:20,098 --> 01:52:22,036
to stay with her.

2059
01:52:22,036 --> 01:52:26,209
She could not spell particularly well butshe found that she could print letters when

2060
01:52:26,209 --> 01:52:30,189
she tried.This was the letter Martha dictated to her:

2061
01:52:30,189 --> 01:52:31,085
"My Dear Dickon:

2062
01:52:31,085 --> 01:52:35,022
This comes hoping to find you well as itleaves me at present.

2063
01:52:35,022 --> 01:52:39,439
Miss Mary has plenty of money and will yougo to Thwaite and buy her some flower seeds

2064
01:52:39,439 --> 01:52:41,066
and a set of garden tools to make a flower-bed.

2065
01:52:41,066 --> 01:52:45,086
Pick the prettiest ones and easy to growbecause she has never done it before and

2066
01:52:45,086 --> 01:52:49,649
lived in India which is different.Give my love to mother and every one of

2067
01:52:49,649 --> 01:52:50,139
you.

2068
01:52:50,139 --> 01:52:54,005
Miss Mary is going to tell me a lot more sothat on my next day out you can hear about

2069
01:52:54,005 --> 01:52:58,209
elephants and camels and gentlemen goinghunting lions and tigers.

2070
01:52:58,209 --> 01:53:01,023
"Your loving sister, Martha PhoebeSowerby."

2071
01:53:01,023 --> 01:53:05,309
"We'll put the money in th' envelope an'I'll get th' butcher boy to take it in his

2072
01:53:05,309 --> 01:53:05,055
cart.

2073
01:53:05,055 --> 01:53:08,529
He's a great friend o' Dickon's," saidMartha.

2074
01:53:08,529 --> 01:53:10,189
"How shall I get the things when Dickonbuys them?"

2075
01:53:10,189 --> 01:53:11,085
"He'll bring 'em to you himself.

2076
01:53:11,085 --> 01:53:17,001
He'll like to walk over this way.""Oh!" exclaimed Mary, "then I shall see

2077
01:53:17,001 --> 01:53:19,149
him!I never thought I should see Dickon."

2078
01:53:19,149 --> 01:53:24,189
"Does tha' want to see him?" asked Marthasuddenly, for Mary had looked so pleased.

2079
01:53:24,189 --> 01:53:27,097
"Yes, I do.I never saw a boy foxes and crows loved.

2080
01:53:27,097 --> 01:53:29,679
I want to see him very much."

2081
01:53:29,679 --> 01:53:32,066
Martha gave a little start, as if sheremembered something.

2082
01:53:32,066 --> 01:53:37,439
"Now to think," she broke out, "to think o'me forgettin' that there; an' I thought I

2083
01:53:37,439 --> 01:53:39,309
was goin' to tell you first thing thismornin'.

2084
01:53:39,309 --> 01:53:42,939
I asked mother--and she said she'd ask Mrs.Medlock her own self."

2085
01:53:42,939 --> 01:53:45,759
"Do you mean--" Mary began."What I said Tuesday.

2086
01:53:45,759 --> 01:53:50,259
Ask her if you might be driven over to ourcottage some day and have a bit o' mother's

2087
01:53:50,259 --> 01:53:53,449
hot oat cake, an' butter, an' a glass o'milk."

2088
01:53:53,449 --> 01:53:57,279
It seemed as if all the interesting thingswere happening in one day.

2089
01:53:57,279 --> 01:54:01,016
To think of going over the moor in thedaylight and when the sky was blue!

2090
01:54:01,016 --> 01:54:04,399
To think of going into the cottage whichheld twelve children!

2091
01:54:04,399 --> 01:54:08,008
"Does she think Mrs. Medlock would let mego?" she asked, quite anxiously.

2092
01:54:08,008 --> 01:54:10,119
"Aye, she thinks she would.

2093
01:54:10,119 --> 01:54:14,899
She knows what a tidy woman mother is andhow clean she keeps the cottage."

2094
01:54:14,899 --> 01:54:19,499
"If I went I should see your mother as wellas Dickon," said Mary, thinking it over and

2095
01:54:19,499 --> 01:54:21,029
liking the idea very much.

2096
01:54:21,029 --> 01:54:24,069
"She doesn't seem to be like the mothers inIndia."

2097
01:54:24,069 --> 01:54:28,091
Her work in the garden and the excitementof the afternoon ended by making her feel

2098
01:54:28,091 --> 01:54:30,055
quiet and thoughtful.

2099
01:54:30,055 --> 01:54:34,899
Martha stayed with her until tea-time, butthey sat in comfortable quiet and talked

2100
01:54:34,899 --> 01:54:37,989
very little.But just before Martha went downstairs for

2101
01:54:37,989 --> 01:54:40,139
the tea-tray, Mary asked a question.

2102
01:54:40,139 --> 01:54:44,699
"Martha," she said, "has the scullery-maidhad the toothache again today?"

2103
01:54:44,699 --> 01:54:50,006
Martha certainly started slightly."What makes thee ask that?" she said.

2104
01:54:50,006 --> 01:54:54,189
"Because when I waited so long for you tocome back I opened the door and walked down

2105
01:54:54,189 --> 01:54:59,001
the corridor to see if you were coming.And I heard that far-off crying again, just

2106
01:54:59,001 --> 01:55:00,809
as we heard it the other night.

2107
01:55:00,809 --> 01:55:05,022
There isn't a wind today, so you see itcouldn't have been the wind."

2108
01:55:05,022 --> 01:55:08,529
"Eh!" said Martha restlessly."Tha' mustn't go walkin' about in corridors

2109
01:55:08,529 --> 01:55:09,066
an' listenin'.

2110
01:55:09,066 --> 01:55:13,249
Mr. Craven would be that there angrythere's no knowin' what he'd do."

2111
01:55:13,249 --> 01:55:17,649
"I wasn't listening," said Mary."I was just waiting for you--and I heard

2112
01:55:17,649 --> 01:55:18,029
it.

2113
01:55:18,029 --> 01:55:20,098
That's three times.""My word!

2114
01:55:20,098 --> 01:55:25,319
There's Mrs. Medlock's bell," said Martha,and she almost ran out of the room.

2115
01:55:25,319 --> 01:55:30,799
"It's the strangest house any one everlived in," said Mary drowsily, as she

2116
01:55:30,799 --> 01:55:34,629
dropped her head on the cushioned seat ofthe armchair near her.

2117
01:55:34,629 --> 01:55:39,319
Fresh air, and digging, and skipping-ropehad made her feel so comfortably tired that

2118
01:55:39,319 --> 01:55:43,075
she fell asleep.

