01:55:44,075 --> 01:55:52,083
CHAPTER XDICKON

2121
01:55:52,083 --> 01:55:56,036
The sun shone down for nearly a week on thesecret garden.

2122
01:55:56,036 --> 01:55:59,073
The Secret Garden was what Mary called itwhen she was thinking of it.

2123
01:55:59,073 --> 01:56:04,011
She liked the name, and she liked stillmore the feeling that when its beautiful

2124
01:56:04,011 --> 01:56:07,074
old walls shut her in no one knew where shewas.

2125
01:56:07,074 --> 01:56:12,067
It seemed almost like being shut out of theworld in some fairy place.

2126
01:56:12,067 --> 01:56:17,016
The few books she had read and liked hadbeen fairy-story books, and she had read of

2127
01:56:17,016 --> 01:56:19,066
secret gardens in some of the stories.

2128
01:56:19,066 --> 01:56:23,076
Sometimes people went to sleep in them fora hundred years, which she had thought must

2129
01:56:23,076 --> 01:56:25,329
be rather stupid.

2130
01:56:25,329 --> 01:56:29,929
She had no intention of going to sleep,and, in fact, she was becoming wider awake

2131
01:56:29,929 --> 01:56:32,044
every day which passed at Misselthwaite.

2132
01:56:32,044 --> 01:56:36,042
She was beginning to like to be out ofdoors; she no longer hated the wind, but

2133
01:56:36,042 --> 01:56:40,039
enjoyed it.She could run faster, and longer, and she

2134
01:56:40,039 --> 01:56:41,969
could skip up to a hundred.

2135
01:56:41,969 --> 01:56:44,999
The bulbs in the secret garden must havebeen much astonished.

2136
01:56:44,999 --> 01:56:49,229
Such nice clear places were made round themthat they had all the breathing space they

2137
01:56:49,229 --> 01:56:53,088
wanted, and really, if Mistress Mary hadknown it, they began to cheer up under the

2138
01:56:53,088 --> 01:56:56,059
dark earth and work tremendously.

2139
01:56:56,059 --> 01:57:00,057
The sun could get at them and warm them,and when the rain came down it could reach

2140
01:57:00,057 --> 01:57:03,619
them at once, so they began to feel verymuch alive.

2141
01:57:03,619 --> 01:57:09,084
Mary was an odd, determined little person,and now she had something interesting to be

2142
01:57:09,084 --> 01:57:13,013
determined about, she was very muchabsorbed, indeed.

2143
01:57:13,013 --> 01:57:17,689
She worked and dug and pulled up weedssteadily, only becoming more pleased with

2144
01:57:17,689 --> 01:57:19,084
her work every hour instead of tiring ofit.

2145
01:57:19,084 --> 01:57:24,369
It seemed to her like a fascinating sort ofplay.

2146
01:57:24,369 --> 01:57:28,979
She found many more of the sprouting palegreen points than she had ever hoped to

2147
01:57:28,979 --> 01:57:29,052
find.

2148
01:57:29,052 --> 01:57:33,089
They seemed to be starting up everywhereand each day she was sure she found tiny

2149
01:57:33,089 --> 01:57:38,001
new ones, some so tiny that they barelypeeped above the earth.

2150
01:57:38,001 --> 01:57:43,179
There were so many that she remembered whatMartha had said about the "snowdrops by the

2151
01:57:43,179 --> 01:57:47,002
thousands," and about bulbs spreading andmaking new ones.

2152
01:57:47,002 --> 01:57:51,439
These had been left to themselves for tenyears and perhaps they had spread, like the

2153
01:57:51,439 --> 01:57:55,679
snowdrops, into thousands.She wondered how long it would be before

2154
01:57:55,679 --> 01:57:58,031
they showed that they were flowers.

2155
01:57:58,031 --> 01:58:01,068
Sometimes she stopped digging to look atthe garden and try to imagine what it would

2156
01:58:01,068 --> 01:58:04,081
be like when it was covered with thousandsof lovely things in bloom.

2157
01:58:04,081 --> 01:58:10,379
During that week of sunshine, she becamemore intimate with Ben Weatherstaff.

2158
01:58:10,379 --> 01:58:14,092
She surprised him several times by seemingto start up beside him as if she sprang out

2159
01:58:14,092 --> 01:58:16,033
of the earth.

2160
01:58:16,033 --> 01:58:19,083
